1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 a6 $5 {This is quite a tricky move. It works well for Najdorf
players. Black also wants to continue with a quick b5, which is a good
strategy against an early Nc3. The drawback of this move is that Black is not
developing a piece and lose some time. I think that White's best chance to
fight for an advantage is to continue with 3.g3.} (2... g6 {Interesting
attempt to enter the Accelerated Dragon where White can't play the Marozcy
System. White can choose between many setups, but I think that the most
practical one is:} 3. d4 cxd4 (3... Bg7 {this is also possible and I include a
few examples, but White is just better here after:} 4. dxc5 Bxc3+ (4... Qa5 5.
Bd2 Qxc5 6. Nd5) 5. bxc3 Qa5 6. Qd4 {[%cal Rd4b4]}) 4. Qxd4 Nf6 5. Be3 $1 {
I found this move a perfect practical chance, and just a few days after my
lecture Magnus Carlsen confirms my conclusion by choosing it and scores a very
easy win against Duda.} Nc6 6. Qd2 Bg7 7. f3 O-O 8. O-O-O {This was my
original idea and I still believe that it is quite good. White has a simple
plan: h4-h5 followed by Bh6, but I also like very much Magnus' idea to keep
the king on e1.} (8. Nge2 $1 {Keeping the king on e1 and still intending to
continue with h4-h5}) 8... d6 9. Nge2) 3. g3 b5 (3... Nc6 {if Black didn't
play 3...b5 White can play the Closed Sicilian where the move 2...a6 will be
just a waste of time.}) 4. Bg2 Bb7 5. d3 e6 6. Nh3 $1 {The key idea for the
variation. White's knight is perfectly placed. From "h3", he can go to f4 or
g5, but even "f2" is a perfect square in some cases. Black is at a crossroad
and should choose between two setups: 1. The setups with d5 2. The setups with
d6 The first one is more active but quite risky. The second is calm, but
passive.} *

