1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 a6 3. g3 b5 4. Bg2 Bb7 5. d3 e6 6. Nh3 Nf6 7. O-O b4 8. Na4 {
The knight is well placed on "a4" in this line. Keeping the diagonal d1-h5
free for White's queen, but also put pressure on c5.} (8. Ne2 {Is another way
of handling this position which we will analyze in the following games.}) 8...
d6 {I believe that Black's setups with d6 are not exactly in the spirit of the
position. The game is more positional than in the -d5 lines. Black's position
seems a bit passive to me. White should slightly gain some space on the
kingside with the typical g4-g5 and the h3-knight has a good spot on f2. After
that, White can try to organize a kingside attack or to open the game in an
appropriate moment.} (8... Bc6 {should be met with} 9. e5 Bxg2 10. Kxg2 Nd5 11.
c4 $14 {White is slightly better}) 9. c3 bxc3 {One of the key ideas for White
is to open the queenside. The rook can be quite useful on the open b-file} 10.
bxc3 Nbd7 11. Nb2 $6 (11. Re1 {I like this move more. The knight on "a4" is
not that bad.} Bc6 12. d4 (12. Nf4 $1 {is a fascinating idea. If Black
continues developing by} Be7 13. e5 $1 {comes out of nowhere} Nxe5 14. d4 Bxa4
15. Qxa4+ $18 Ned7 16. Rxe6 $1 fxe6 17. Nxe6 Qc8 18. Bxa8 $18) 12... cxd4 13.
cxd4 d5 $2 (13... Qa5 $1 {was the only move} 14. Nb2 d5 15. e5 $14) 14. exd5
Bxd5 15. Nf4 Bxg2 16. Kxg2 $16 {Now Black can't stop the advance d4-d5 and his
position is falling a part} Qa5 17. d5 e5 18. d6 Qb4 19. Bb2 (19. Nd3 $1 Qxd6
20. Qf3 $18 {[%cal Rc1f4]}) 19... Bxd6 20. Rb1 Qb7+ 21. Kg1 Qc7 22. Nd5 Nxd5
23. Qxd5 Rd8 24. Bc3 $16 {1/2 (60)-1/2 (60) Xiong,J (2700)-Swiercz,D (2647)
Saint Louis 2021}) 11... Be7 12. f4 Qc7 13. Nf2 (13. g4 $1 {is the logical
follow-up. White shouldn't be afraid of} h5 14. g5 Ng4 15. Nf2 $1 {forcing the
exchange of the knights and leaving the Black's kingside pawn structure
compromised}) 13... h6 14. Be3 Rb8 15. Qd2 d5 {Black is afraid to castle, but
this advance helps more White} (15... Bc6 {followed by the advance of the
a-pawn and 0-0 at some moment}) (15... O-O {The engines like this move, but
from a human move g4-g5 threat looks quite dangerous}) 16. e5 d4 (16... Nh7 17.
d4 $14 {The space advantage gives White better chances. The advance f4-f5 is
in the air.}) 17. cxd4 Bxg2 18. Kxg2 Qb7+ 19. Kg1 Qxb2 20. Qxb2 Rxb2 21. exf6
Nxf6 22. dxc5 Kd7 {Black's active pieces should compensate the missing pawn,
but in the game Black failed to save the half point.} 23. d4 $11 Nd5 24. Nd3
Re2 25. Bf2 Bf6 26. Rfe1 Rd2 27. Red1 Rxd1+ 28. Rxd1 Rb8 29. Rc1 Kc6 30. Kg2
Rb5 31. Rc4 Rb1 32. Kf3 a5 33. g4 Rd1 34. Ke2 Ra1 35. Rc2 g5 36. fxg5 hxg5 37.
Kf3 Rh1 38. Kg2 Rd1 39. Nb2 Rb1 40. Nc4 a4 41. Kf3 Nb4 42. Rd2 Rc1 43. Nd6 Ra1
(43... a3 $1 $11 {[%cal Rc1a1]}) 44. Rb2 Nd3 45. Rb6+ Kd5 46. Ne4 (46. Ne8 Nxf2
47. Rd6+ Kc4 48. c6 $16) 46... Nxf2 47. Rd6+ Kc4 48. Nxf6 Rxa2 (48... Nh3 $3 {
this move saves the day} 49. c6 Kd3 50. c7 Rf1+ 51. Kg2 Ke2 $3 {the point of
Blacks idea} 52. Kxh3 Rf3+ 53. Kg2 Rf2+ $11) 49. c6 Rc2 50. c7 Kd3 51. d5 Rxc7
52. dxe6+ Kc2 53. Nd5 Ra7 54. Rd7 fxe6 55. Rxa7 1-0

