{[%evp 0,119,20,5,50,49,67,36,58,51,63,55,50,26,33,25,32,34,16,5,-1,23,18,-5,
-2,3,3,-47,-2,-34,7,2,2,6,24,49,52,51,43,51,80,62,68,64,50,46,24,29,45,47,50,
30,76,58,65,41,73,85,90,104,104,99,113,111,107,106,107,65,96,83,96,83,83,80,84,
84,66,61,61,104,115,94,107,120,122,104,161,155,154,159,189,201,194,179,178,174,
170,145,152,118,124,138,131,124,124,134,126,376,384,190,320,314,500,712,1134,
1356,1491,1719,1984,1919,2212,2413]} 1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 a6 3. g3 b5 4. Bg2 Bb7 5.
d3 e6 6. Nh3 Nf6 7. O-O d6 {As we already mentioned in the previous game the
system with "d6" is not bad, but passive. In this game GM Vitugov manages to
convert his small advantage to a full point.} 8. f4 b4 9. Ne2 {If the pawn is
already on "d6" and the c5-pawn is protected, White's knight is better placed
on "e2" than on "a4"} Be7 10. Nf2 Nc6 11. g4 Nd7 12. a3 (12. c3 {I like this
move more, because it is not only challenging the "b4" pawn, but is preparing
the d4 advance as well.}) 12... a5 13. Ng3 Qb6 14. axb4 axb4 15. Rxa8+ Bxa8 16.
g5 {After the exchange of his useless rook, White continues the advancing of
his pawns on the kingside. As you saw in the previous game, Black is always
afraid to castle in this line.} Nd4 17. c3 {this move was good anyways, but
Black is even provoking it} bxc3 18. bxc3 Nb5 19. Bd2 g6 20. h4 (20. Qa1 $1 {
Switching the action to the queenside puts Black on the edge} Bc6 21. Rb1 $16)
20... h6 $1 21. Qa1 {Vitugov finds the idea one move later, but this is a
better version for Black, because he has some counterplay on the kingside} Bc6
22. Be3 hxg5 23. hxg5 Qa7 24. Qxa7 Nxa7 25. d4 {The Russian GM lost a big part
of his advantage, but even without queens, Black is suffering the lack of space
} Nb6 26. dxc5 dxc5 27. Rb1 Nd7 28. e5 Kd8 29. Ra1 Bxg2 30. Kxg2 Nc8 31. Nge4
Kc7 32. Ng4 Ncb6 {Even if this position is holdable for Black, it is tough to
play. The f7-pawn is an eternal weakness. White has a long-term initiative and
he manages to win the game 30 moves later} 33. Ngf6 Kb7 34. Kg3 Bf8 35. Rd1 Kc6
36. Nxd7 Nxd7 37. Nf6 Nb6 38. Rd8 Bg7 39. Rd6+ Kb5 40. Ne4 Nc4 41. Rd3 Bf8 42.
Bf2 Be7 43. Rd7 $18 Re8 44. Rc7 Nb6 45. Nf6 Bxf6 46. Rxc5+ Ka6 47. gxf6 Na8 48.
Rc6+ Kb7 49. Rd6 Rc8 50. Bd4 Rc6 51. Rd7+ Rc7 52. Re7 Rxe7 53. fxe7 Nc7 54. Kg4
Kc6 55. c4 Kd7 56. Bc5 Na8 57. Kg5 Ke8 58. Kf6 Nc7 59. Bd6 Na6 60. Kg7 1-0

