1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 g6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Qxd4 Nf6 5. Be3 Bg7 6. Qd2 O-O 7. O-O-O Nc6 8.
f3 d6 9. Nge2 {We reach a positional from Classical Dragon, but with the
knight on e2 instead of d4. You can argue that the knight is more passive here
and blocks the bishop, but on the other hand, Black doesn't have the ideas
with Rxc3 or with Nxd4. White's play is quite simple - h4-h5 followed by hxg6
and Bh6. In many cases the knight from e2 can go to f4 to support the attack}
Qa5 10. Kb1 Be6 11. Bh6 (11. Nf4 $1 $16) 11... Bxh6 12. Qxh6 Rac8 13. h4 Ne5
14. h5 Nc4 {The game becomes very sharp and Black has his chances, but in the
end, White manages to win after a lot of adventures} 15. hxg6 fxg6 16. Rd3 Bf7
17. f4 Rc5 18. Nc1 Qb6 19. Nb3 Rh5 20. Rxh5 Nxh5 21. g4 Qf2 $2 22. gxh5 Qxf1+
23. Rd1 Qh3 24. Qg5 Ne3 25. Rc1 Qxh5 26. Qxe7 Bxb3 27. axb3 Rxf4 28. Qxd6 Qf3
29. Qb8+ Kg7 30. Qxa7 Rf7 31. Qd4+ Kg8 32. Re1 Ng2 33. Rd1 Ne3 34. Re1 Ng2 35.
Rc1 Nf4 36. Qc4 g5 37. Nb5 Qe2 38. Qc5 g4 39. Nd6 Rf8 40. Qc7 Ne6 41. Qxb7 g3
42. Qd5 Rf6 43. e5 Qh5 44. Ne4 Rg6 45. Nxg3 Qh2 46. Nf5 Kh8 47. Ne7 Rg1 48.
Qa8+ 1-0

