1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 g6 {This is a tricky move. If White continues with Nf3, we
will reach an Accelerated Dragon, but Black avoids the dangerous Marozcy
System. White, of course, can continue with 3.f4 or 3.g3 but those moves lead
to systems that are out of the scope of our camp. That's why I choose to show
you the most direct approach - 3.d4} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Qxd4 Nf6 5. Be3 (5. Nf3 {
This leads to a heavy analyzed position, which can be reached after 2.Nf3 g6
move order, but I don't think that this is an excellent practical choice and I
can't find an advantage there}) (5. e5 Nc6 6. Qf4 Nh5 {Black is doing quite
well here in practice}) 5... Nc6 6. Qd2 d6 7. f3 Bg7 8. Nge2 {In the lecture
and the other games, White started with 0-0-0, but this relatively recent game
by Magnus shows a new way to handle the position. He delayed castling and
started with an immediate attack against Black's king by means of h4-h5} Be6 9.
Nf4 O-O 10. h4 $1 {The play once again resembles the Dragon variation} Ne5 (
10... h5 {is not good either} 11. Nxe6 fxe6 12. O-O-O {[%csl Rg6] Now the
g6-pawn is very weak}) 11. h5 Bc4 12. hxg6 hxg6 (12... fxg6 {is ugly, but it
is the only move which is not losing}) 13. Nd3 $1 $18 {Now Bh6 is unstoppable
and it is game over} Be6 14. Bh6 Nh5 15. Bxg7 Kxg7 16. Rxh5 gxh5 17. Nxe5 dxe5
18. Qg5+ Kh7 19. Qxh5+ Kg8 20. Bd3 {[%cal Rh5g5,Re1e2,Ra1h1]} 1-0

