{[%evp 0,86,18,30,46,46,81,49,49,40,40,28,28,2,28,29,20,20,23,23,23,13,17,7,0,
0,5,4,11,-11,-4,0,-1,-3,-4,2,2,6,25,18,18,18,31,41,23,40,44,47,43,64,66,66,64,
64,64,72,70,67,68,63,68,68,65,46,57,58,61,65,65,66,69,77,104,122,107,117,110,
105,105,114,114,114,122,72,66,26,104,127,104] We will first start dealing with
the Scheveningen setups based on ...e7-e6. In my opinion, Carlsen Variation is
very effective when Black is playing in a typical Scheveningen fashion.
Therefore, when top players play ...e7-e6, they usually associate this move
with the quick ...d6-d5. In the next few games, I will try to provide
different options to fight against this system. The first model game shows how
White can play for a slight advantage in an endgame with IQP. This game is a
nice performance by Nakamura.} 1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Qxd4 Nc6 5. Qd2
Nf6 6. b3 e6 7. Bb2 {White is ready to proceed with 0-0-0 followed by f2-f4
with very good attacking prospects on the kingside. Therefore, MVL strikes
immediately} d5 {Now is probably the most suitable moment for this break. If
White is allowed to play f2-f4. the advance ...d6-d5 can be answered with
e4-e5, thus going for a French structure that we are going to examine a bit
later.} 8. exd5 exd5 9. O-O-O Be6 10. Kb1 {[%csl Ba2][%cal Bd8a5,Bc3b5,Bf1d3,
Bg1f3,Bh1e1,Bf2f3,Bg2g4,Bh2h4] This move is White's most solid way of handling
the position. By overprotecting the a2-pawn, White is getting ready to answer .
..Qa5 with Nb5, forcing the transition into an endgame. Of course, White has
alternative setups that we are going to explore in the next examples.} Qa5 11.
Nb5 Qxd2 12. Rxd2 {[%csl Be4,Bb2][%cal Bb5d4,Bf2f3,Bf6e4,Bg2g4,Bh2h4,Bg4g5,
Bf1d3,Bg1e2] Let's try to evaluate this typical endgame position. If White
manages to stabilize his position and neutralize the temporary activity of the
black minor pieces, he would enjoy better long-term prospects due to the
vulnerable d5-pawn. After securing a stable control of the d4-squares (with
moves such as Nd4 followed by Bd3 and Nge2), White can start winning space on
the kingside. A typical way to do so would be f2-f3 followed by g2-g4, and
h2-h4. The kingside expansion should be combined with pressure on the d5-pawn.
On the other hand, Black should be trying to transform his piece activity into
some kind of a static achievement.} Ne4 {This is probably not the most precise
move as White wants to play f2-f3 anyway.} ({In my opinion, the critical would
have been} 12... Bb4 {when White should play} 13. Rd3 {[%csl Be2][%cal Bb5d4,
Bf2f3,Bg1e2,Bd3d1] leaving the e2-square for the knight.} ({The problem with} 
13. Rd1 $2 {is that after} Ne4 14. Nc7+ Kd7 15. Nxe6 Nxf2 {Black makes use of
the fact that the d1-rook is unprotected.}) 13... O-O-O (13... O-O 14. Bxf6
gxf6 15. Ne2 Rac8 16. Nbd4 Rfe8 $14 {Even though the position remains
complicated, in the long-term, White's static advantage will outweigh Black's
activity.}) ({In comparison with 13.Rd1, in the line} 13... Ne4 14. Nc7+ Kd7
15. Nxe6 {Black's ...Nxf2 is not effective since the white rook is protected
on d3.} fxe6 16. Nh3 $14 {White enjoys a slight advantage since Black's
central pawns are potentially vulnerable.}) 14. Nd4 Ne4 15. Nxe6 fxe6 16. Nh3 {
[%csl Bf1,Bb2,Bd5,Be6][%cal Be4d2,Bd2f1,Bh1f1] Once again, we reach this
typical structure in which White's hopes of advantage are based on the active
b2-bishop and Black's vulnerable central pawns. Even with the best possible
play (according to Stockfish), Black cannot solve the problems entirely. A
possible line would be -} e5 17. a3 Be1 18. f3 Nd2+ 19. Ka2 Nxf1 20. Rxf1 Bh4 {
[%csl Be5,Bd5,Be4][%cal Bh4f6,Bd5d4]} 21. Rfd1 {White wants to provoke the
advance ...d5-d4. In this case, the e4-square, as well as the e5-pawn, will be
weak.} d4 22. R3d2 $14 {[%csl Be5,Bd3][%cal Bh3f2,Bf2e4,Bf2d3,Bd2e2,Bd1e1]
White is slightly better. Ideally, he would transfer the knight to d3 and
double the rooks along the e-file, thus putting tremendous pressure on the
e5-pawn.}) 13. Re2 O-O-O 14. f3 a6 15. Nd4 Nxd4 16. Bxd4 Bc5 {The most
straightforward continuation. Black challenges White's control of the
d4-square.} ({Worse is} 16... Nf6 17. Rd2 {[%cal Bf1d3,Bg1e2,Bg2g4,Bh2h4] when
White has a huge advantage. After Rd2 and Bd3, he can already start gaining
space on the kingside. In such positions, the knight is badly placed on f6 due
to the f3-pawn.}) 17. Bxc5 Nxc5 18. Rd2 {Besides, blocking the isolated pawn
with the knight, White can also try to capture it. Therefore, putting the
knight on f4, b4 or c3 is also possible in such positions. In the endgame,
instead of blocking the pawn, it's enough to just control the square in front
of it.} Rhe8 ({Preventing White from seizing kingside space with the move} 
18... h5 {is not a good idea in view of} 19. h4 {[%cal Bg1e2,Be2f4,Bg7g6,Bf1e2,
Bh1d1] fixing the h5-pawn. In order to protect it, sooner or later, Black will
be forced to play ...g7-g6, putting all his pawns on the colour of the bishop.}
) 19. Ne2 Bf5 {[%cal Be2d4,Be8e1,Gc5e6] We can now see the entire concept
behind 16...Bc5. Black wants to fight for the d4-square by means of ...Ne6.}
20. Kb2 {[%cal Be2d4,Bf1e2,Bh1d1]} Ne6 21. g4 {This natural move is quite
thematic in such positions.} ({Another option would have been} 21. h4 $5 {
[%cal Bg2g4,Bh4h5] with the idea to provoke} h5 {when after} 22. Ng3 Bg6 23.
Bd3 {[%csl Bh5][%cal Bh1d1] the piece exchanges will make Black's weaknesses
even more significant.}) 21... Bg6 22. h4 h6 23. Bg2 {In a favourable moment,
White is ready to proceed with f3-f4. MVL decided to play actively with} d4 24.
Rhd1 d3 {but after} 25. cxd3 Nd4 26. Nxd4 Rxd4 27. Kc3 {It turns out that
Black does not have enough compensation for the pawn. Later on, White managed
to convert his advantage.} Red8 28. h5 Bh7 29. Bf1 Rf4 30. Be2 f5 31. Rg1 Rd7
32. g5 Rh4 33. gxh6 gxh6 34. d4 Rxh5 35. Bc4 Kc7 36. Rdg2 f4 37. Be6 Re7 38.
Rg7 Kd6 39. Rxe7 Kxe7 40. Bc8 Bf5 41. Bxf5 Rxf5 42. Rg7+ Kf6 43. Rxb7 h5 44.
Kc4 Kg6 45. d5 h4 46. d6 h3 47. Re7 Rf8 48. Kd5 Rh8 49. Re1 Kg5 50. d7 Rd8 51.
Kc6 Kh4 52. Re8 {1-0 Black resigns.} 1-0

