{[%evp 0,123,27,15,51,50,94,40,40,41,41,30,21,-11,29,21,23,23,23,7,4,15,16,0,5,
5,10,9,0,-16,9,18,25,5,4,6,9,10,17,15,57,56,52,49,46,56,48,51,51,-20,-9,0,0,0,
41,57,63,40,40,36,36,57,57,38,57,53,51,44,50,70,73,78,113,64,79,55,133,132,118,
137,136,130,132,124,119,122,127,143,145,169,171,177,180,193,192,188,167,172,
184,184,184,147,230,240,235,291,291,70,152,226,234,234,248,276,290,290,290,317,
339,340,678,383,387,388,406,409] The following example shows that in the IQP
endgame, playing for domination is often better than just going for the
material. The first 14 moves repeat the previous example -} 1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 d6
3. d4 cxd4 4. Qxd4 Nc6 5. Qd2 Nf6 6. b3 e6 7. Bb2 d5 8. exd5 exd5 9. O-O-O {
[%cal Bc1b1]} Be6 10. Kb1 Qa5 11. Nb5 Qxd2 12. Rxd2 Ne4 13. Re2 O-O-O 14. f3 {
Now, instead of 14...a6 played by MVL, here Black played} Nf6 {[%csl Bd4,Bb5]
[%cal Bd5d4,Bf8c5,Bf6d5] As I have pointed out in my comments to the previous
example, on f6, the knight is heavily restricted by the f3-pawn. In this case,
Black does not have any dynamic counterplay. In the next few moves, White
manages to easily stabilize his position -} 15. Nd4 Bd7 16. Rd2 Bb4 17. Rd1
Rhe8 18. Nge2 {[%cal Gh2h4] Now, White is in full control. The next step is to
start the thematic kingside expansion with h2-h4.} ({Another good option is} 
18. Bd3 {[%cal Bg1e2] planning to answer} Ne5 {[%csl Bd3] with} 19. Nge2 {
In this structure, you should be never afraid of exchanging your light-squared
bishop for one of the black knights. First of all, Black needs his knights in
order to create dynamic counterplay. Secondly, all exchanges of minor pieces
favour the side playing against IQP. After} Nxd3 20. Rxd3 {[%csl Bd5,Bd7][%cal
Bh1d1,Bg2g4,Bh2h4,Be2f4,Bg4g5] White is ready to combine his kingside play
with a pressure on d5.}) 18... Kb8 19. h4 {[%cal Bh4h5,Bh5h6] Besides g2-g4,
Black should also reckon with the idea of h4-h5-h6.} h5 {[%csl Bh5] Provoking
this advance is always a small victory for White.} 20. Ng3 Bd6 {This is the
critical position. In the game, White played} 21. Nxc6+ $6 {with the idea to
win a pawn.} ({Nevertheless, playing for domination would have been better.
For example, after} 21. Ndf5 $1 Bf8 22. Bxf6 gxf6 23. Bd3 $16 {Black is
completely busted. The h5-pawn will fall anyway.}) 21... bxc6 22. Bxf6 gxf6 23.
Nxh5 Be5 $44 {[%csl Bd5,Be5,Bd7][%cal Be8h8] Black's bishop pair, active
pieces, and good central control provide enough compensation for the pawn.
Nevertheless, White finally managed to win the game.} 24. Bd3 Rh8 25. g4 f5 26.
Be2 fxg4 27. fxg4 f5 28. g5 Be8 29. Nf6 Bxf6 30. gxf6 Rd6 31. c4 Rxf6 32. cxd5
cxd5 33. Bf3 Rfh6 34. Rd4 Bh5 35. Bxd5 Bg4 36. Re1 Rxh4 37. Re7 Bh3 38. Rb7+
Kc8 39. Rxh4 Rxh4 40. Rxa7 Rd4 41. Be6+ Kd8 42. a4 Rd6 43. Bc4 Rf6 44. Rh7 Bg4
45. Rg7 Bf3 46. a5 f4 47. a6 Be4+ 48. Kb2 f3 49. a7 f2 50. Bf1 Re6 51. Rf7 Re7
52. Rf8+ Kc7 53. a8=Q Bxa8 54. Rxa8 Re1 55. Ra1 Kb6 56. b4 Re4 57. b5 Re1 58.
Rc1 Ka5 59. Kc2 Kb4 60. Kd2 Re6 61. Rc4+ Ka5 62. Rf4 {1-0 Black resigns.} 1-0

