{[%evp 0,97,17,13,36,50,78,38,38,45,46,28,28,-5,20,27,23,23,26,26,12,5,15,15,
15,7,28,22,35,7,24,7,7,-3,3,-9,36,36,27,-37,16,35,42,57,66,15,38,30,46,46,51,
61,55,37,39,24,24,22,22,22,25,11,6,7,7,15,61,66,56,56,52,50,50,58,58,53,58,40,
36,42,54,41,43,55,53,53,53,53,115,0,0,0,2,0,0,0,0,0,0,0] As we have already
seen, playing 10.Kb1 is a concept that is solid and good enough. Nevertheless,
when you study a given opening, you always need to have alternatives. In this
way, besides making the preparation of your opponent very difficult, you will
get a better feeling of the entire variation. In the next three examples, I
will provide some alternative ways of playing for White. After studying all
the main ideas and possibilities, you need to start looking for your own ways.
I strongly encourage you to create your own theory in the variations that you
play and study.} 1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Qxd4 Nc6 5. Qd2 Nf6 6. b3 e6
7. Bb2 d5 8. exd5 exd5 9. O-O-O Be6 10. a3 {[%csl Bb2][%cal Bf1d3,Bg1f3,Bd2f4,
Bh1e1,Bf3g5,Bh2h4] This is another way to fight against the idea of ...Qa5.
White just wants to answer the early sortie of the black queen with b3-b4.
With queens on the board, White has decent chances to develop a kingside
attack. He can follow with simple moves such as Nf3, Bd3, and Qf4.} Bc5 {
This active move seems to be pretty natural.} ({An important line is} 10... Qa5
11. b4 Qc7 12. Nge2 {[%csl Bd5][%cal Bg2g3,Bf1g2,Be2d4] planning to besiege
the isolated pawn with g2-g3 followed by Bg2 and Nd4. A possible follow up
could be} a6 13. g3 O-O-O 14. Nd4 Nxd4 15. Qxd4 $14 {with an advantage for
White. White has better structure and more active pieces. Black cannot
challenge the centralized queen.}) ({In my opinion, the most critical setup is
} 10... Bd6 {[%cal Gd8e7] planning to put pressure on a3 by means of ...Qe7.}
11. Nf3 {[%cal Bf1d3,Bh1e1,Bc3b5,Bf3d4] I find this natural developing move to
be the most precise reaction.} ({Trying to defend the pawn with} 11. Kb1 Qe7
12. Qc1 {seems to be too passive. After} O-O-O 13. Bd3 a6 $132 {Black has
decent counterplay.}) 11... Qe7 12. Nb5 Bc5 13. Bd3 {White is ready to
sacrifice the a3-pawn in order to fight for an initiative.} ({An interesting
alternative is} 13. b4 Bb6 14. Re1 a6 15. Nbd4 Ne4 16. Qf4 O-O 17. Bd3 $13 {
with an unclear position which is playable for both sides.}) 13... a6 14. Nbd4
Bxa3 15. Rhe1 {In return for the pawn, White managed to put significant
pressure. Black should play precisely in order to balance the game. The most
precise reaction seems to be} O-O 16. Bf5 Ne4 $1 {This is the key move. Black
gives the pawn back in order to neutralize White's activity. After} 17. Bxe4
dxe4 18. Rxe4 Rfd8 $132 {the position is balanced.}) 11. Nf3 O-O 12. Bd3 Rc8
13. Rhe1 Re8 {[%csl Bd3] Both sides managed to mobilize their forces to the
maximum. White should now decide on the further course of the game. Caruana
played} 14. h3 {which, in my opinion, is too slow.} ({More to the point would
have been} 14. Nb5 {[%csl Bd4] taking control of the d4-square. Black should
probably play} Bf8 ({Due to the vulnerable c5-bishop, Black cannot play} 14...
Ne4 $2 {After} 15. Bxe4 dxe4 16. Qc3 {[%csl Bg7,Bd8,Bc5][%cal Bd1d8] White is
just winning.}) 15. Nfd4 Bd7 16. Nf5 $16 {[%csl Bb2,Bd3]}) {In my opinion,
after 14.h3, White cannot fight for an advantage. Therefore, the remaining
part of the game will be left without comments.} 14... Qa5 (14... a6) 15. Nb5
Qxd2+ 16. Rxd2 a6 17. Nbd4 Ne4 18. Rde2 Bd7 19. Kd1 f6 20. Nxc6 Bxc6 21. Nd4
Bd7 22. f3 Ng3 23. Rxe8+ Rxe8 24. c4 dxc4 25. Bxc4+ Kf8 26. b4 Bd6 27. Ne6+
Bxe6 28. Rxe6 Rd8 29. Kc2 Nh5 30. Re4 b5 31. Bd3 Nf4 32. Bf1 Re8 33. Kb3 Rxe4
34. fxe4 Ne6 35. a4 Nc7 36. Bd4 Ke7 37. Be2 Kd7 38. Be3 Be5 39. h4 g6 40. h5
gxh5 41. Bxh5 Ne6 42. Bg4 Kd6 43. a5 Nd4+ 44. Ka2 Kc7 45. Bf2 Nc2 46. Kb3 Nd4+
47. Ka2 Nc2 48. Kb3 Nd4+ 49. Ka2 {1/2-1/2 The game is a draw.} 1/2-1/2

