{[%evp 0,67,19,20,45,51,71,45,43,40,43,22,28,9,15,15,15,15,15,15,34,19,36,14,
36,9,9,-61,6,-73,-46,-34,-34,-34,-36,-29,-30,-30,-32,-32,-32,-32,-35,-17,22,22,
22,21,25,50,60,68,43,38,38,38,29,0,357,314,571,593,617,658,29987,29988,29989,
29990,29995,29996] In this example, White goes for a quick development without
even paying attention to ...Qa5 idea. Even though, Black is probably doing
fine, the arising positions are practically easier for White.} 1. e4 c5 2. Nc3
d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Qxd4 Nc6 5. Qd2 e6 6. b3 Nf6 7. Bb2 d5 8. exd5 exd5 9. O-O-O
Be6 10. Nf3 {White can be more natural than this developing move. White is
going for a quick mobilization of his forces.} Qa5 {[%cal Bc3b5,Ba5a2]} 11. Nd4
{A very logical move. Depending on the concrete circumstances, White can
either play Nxe6 or Bb5.} ({Practically speaking, even more dangerous would
have been} 11. Nb5 {the idea is to answer} Qxa2 {with} 12. Qf4 {In order to
survive, Black should make a number of precise moves.} Rd8 13. Rd4 $1 {[%csl
Bc6][%cal Bf3d4,Bd4a4] Another very strong practical solution. White wants to
eliminate the c6-knight and bring his f3-knight in the centre. The threat is
obviously Ra4, trapping the queen. The price of every move is getting higher
and higher.} Nxd4 14. Nfxd4 {At this point, Black has two decent moves. The
most natural seems to be} Qa5 ({The other possibility is} 14... a6 {when
White's best is} 15. Qc7 axb5 16. Nxe6 fxe6 17. Bxb5+ {Even though the
position looks very scary for Black, everything ends with a draw -} Nd7 18. Re1
Ba3 19. Bxd7+ Rxd7 20. Rxe6+ Re7 21. Rxe7+ Bxe7 22. Qc8+ Kf7 23. Qf5+ $11 {
with a perpetual.}) {The following sequence seems to be pretty much forced.}
15. Nc7+ Kd7 16. Bb5+ Kc8 17. Ncxe6 Bd6 18. Qf5 fxe6 19. Nxe6 Kb8 20. Nxd8 Rxd8
21. Bd3 $13 {Despite the fact that the position is objectively balanced,
White's play seems a bit easier.}) 11... Bb4 12. Nxe6 $6 {Exchanging the
centralized knight is an inaccuracy.} ({The most critical test would have been
} 12. Bb5 O-O {This was Black's choice in the game Liang, A - Ter Sahakyan, S,
2020.} ({Another principled line would have been} 12... Ne4 {In this case,
White should react with} 13. Nxc6 bxc6 14. Bxc6+ Kf8 15. Qe3 {the point being
that} Nxc3 {can be met by} 16. a3 Bxa3 17. Bxa8 {In a practical game, Black
would resign in a few moves but the powerful computer comes up with a
fantastic sequence -} Ke7 $1 18. Qg5+ Kd6 19. Bxd5 Bxd5 20. Rxd5+ Nxd5 21. Qe5+
Kc6 22. Rd1 Rd8 23. c4 Qc5 24. Rxd5 Bxb2+ 25. Kxb2 Rxd5 26. cxd5+ Qxd5 {
with a draw. Possible, you can try to improve White's play.}) 13. Bxc6 Ne4 {
This move practically forces a draw after} 14. Qe3 Nxc3 15. Bxb7 Nxa2+ 16. Kb1
Nc3+ 17. Kc1 Na2+ 18. Kb1 Nc3+ 19. Kc1 Na2+ {1/2-1/2 (19) Liang,A (2592)-Ter
Sahakyan,S (2640) Chess.com INT 2020}) 12... fxe6 $15 {Black is already
slightly better due to his superior central control and queenside attacking
prospects.} 13. Qe3 Kf7 14. Kb1 d4 15. Rxd4 Nxd4 16. Qxd4 Rhd8 17. Qe3 Bxc3 18.
Bxc3 Rd1+ 19. Kb2 Qb6 20. Qf3 Rad8 21. g3 R8d5 22. Bc4 Rxh1 23. Qxh1 Rh5 24. f4
Qc6 25. Qd1 b5 26. Bxf6 Rxh2 27. Bc3 bxc4 28. Qd4 Kg6 29. f5+ exf5 30. Qxg7+
Kh5 31. Qxh7+ Qh6 32. Qxf5+ Qg5 33. g4+ Kh6 34. Qf8+ {1-0 Black resigns.} 1-0

