{[%evp 0,41,19,20,45,37,71,43,36,40,41,24,25,-8,15,15,15,15,15,19,19,19,2,28,0,
-17,7,2,0,10,0,8,8,8,18,18,1,7,7,0,20,6,29,39] As I have already pointed out,
after studying the main ideas as well as the existing theory, you should start
looking for new directions. In this brief example, I just want to suggest a
possible new direction that you can submit to further investigations. After} 1.
e4 c5 2. Nc3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Qxd4 Nc6 5. Qd2 Nf6 6. b3 e6 7. Bb2 d5 8. exd5
exd5 {[%cal Be1c1] Instead of immediately castling long, White can play the
flexible} 9. a3 {[%csl Ba3][%cal Be1c1,Bg1f3,Bf1d3,Be1g1,Bg1e2] which turns
out to be a novelty. In the previous lines, we have seen that Black's
counterplay is often based on moves like ...Qa5 and ...Bb4. Additionally, with
his last move, White keeps the option of castling short. While the bishop will
be most probably developed to d3, the knight can go either to f3 or e2. Long
story short, the position is rich of ideas that you can investigate.} Be6 10.
Bd3 a6 {I think that Black should include this move in order to take the
b5-square under control.} ({After} 10... Bd6 {White can play} 11. Nb5 Be5 12.
Bxe5 Nxe5 13. Ne2 O-O 14. O-O $14 {with a typical slight edge.}) 11. Nf3 Bd6 {
In this position, instead of castling long, I would prefer} 12. O-O O-O 13. h3
Re8 14. Rfe1 $14 {[%csl Bc3,Bb2][%cal Ba1d1,Bc3e2,Be2d4,Bd2c1,Bc1a1] In my
opinion, White is slightly better in this position. In order to establish firm
control of the d4-square, White can carry out the manoeuvre Nc3-e2-d4 followed
by Rad1. At the same time, the queen can be transferred to a1. I hope that my
brief notes might help you to develop your own theory in the line with 9.a3.} *

