{[%evp 0,35,30,17,42,32,66,36,36,36,38,24,33,-8,19,19,13,13,5,4,4,4,4,4,4,4,3,
-3,10,-65,5,5,11,17,17,11,61,3] In the next 3 examples, we are going to deal
with the French structures that might arise from the Scheveningen setup. The
French structure is being reached when White answers the advance ...d6-d5 with
e4-e5 (usually after having played f2-f4).} 1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4.
Qxd4 Nc6 5. Qd2 Nf6 6. b3 e6 7. Bb2 Be7 8. O-O-O O-O 9. f4 {With this move,
White not only prepares his kingside expansion with g2-g4 but is also planning
to answer} d5 {with} 10. e5 Nd7 11. Nf3 {[%csl Bb3,Bc3][%cal Bc8c1,Bh2h4,Bf1d3,
Bf3g5,Bg7g6,Bh4h5,Bh1h3,Bh3c3] This French structure is highly favourable for
White. Having the dark-squared bishop on b2, White shouldn't worry about the
safety of his king. At the same time, Black's queenside counterplay is too
slow. On the other hand, White's kingside attack is pretty straightforward.
There are three key moves in White's attacking concept - Bd3, h2-h4, and Ng5.
The idea is to provoke ...g7-g6. Later on, the g6-pawn will be used as a hook
for the break h4-h5. In general, if White manages to open the position with
h4-h5, the mate follows quite soon. The move h2-h4 is also a prophylactic move.
By playing Rh3 in case of necessity, White would neutralize Black's eventual
pressure on the c3-knight.} a6 12. Kb1 b5 13. h4 Nc5 14. Ng5 {Of course, there
is nothing wrong with this typical move.} ({Probably, even more, precise would
have been} 14. Bd3 b4 {[%cal Bc3e2,Ba6a5,Ba5a4] Black's main idea is to follow
with ...a6-a5-a4.} ({Taking the bishop with} 14... Nxd3 {does not solve the
problems since after} 15. Qxd3 {[%csl Bd3][%cal Bf3g5,Bg7g6,Bh4h5,Bd3h3] the
queen is very well placed on d3.}) 15. Na4 $1 {Remember this typical idea. The
queenside pawn structure will be important only in the endgame. Unfortunately
for Black, however, he will get mated long before the endgame!} Nxa4 16. bxa4 {
[%csl Bb1,Ba4,Ba2,Bc2][%cal Bf3g5] White is ready to follow with Ng5 on the
next move. Actually, all the queenside pawns as well as the b2-bishop provide
the white king with a very nice shelter.}) 14... b4 15. Na4 {Of course!} Nxa4
16. Qd3 {As pointed out in one of my previous comments, d3-square is the
perfect spot for the queen. Therefore, this intermediate move works very well
here.} g6 17. bxa4 {[%cal Gh4h5] Now, Black can do nothing against the threat
of h4-h5.} f5 18. h5 $1 {Of course, keeping the momentum is far more important
than the pawn.} Bxg5 19. fxg5 Qxg5 20. hxg6 Qxg6 21. Qe3 {Of course, this
natural move is good enough to win the game. White is planning to open the
kingside by means of the advance g2-g4.} ({Even more precise would have been} 
21. Qd2 $18 {[%cal Bg2g4,Bf1d3] White is going to follow with Bd3 and g2-g4.})
21... d4 22. Bxd4 Nxd4 23. Rxd4 Ra7 24. g4 Rg7 25. gxf5 exf5 26. Rd6 Qg4 27.
Bd3 Bb7 28. Re1 Qg3 29. Qd2 Be4 30. Rf6 Bxd3 31. Rxf8+ Kxf8 32. cxd3 Re7 33. d4
f4 34. d5 f3 35. e6 Qg6+ 36. Kb2 Qf6+ 37. Kb3 Rc7 38. Qxb4+ Kg7 39. Rg1+ Kh6
40. Qd2+ {1-0 Black resigns.} 1-0

