{[%evp 0,85,30,15,56,48,58,49,49,48,45,26,21,2,12,13,32,11,12,4,4,4,4,8,24,-3,
16,16,3,6,15,-24,-2,-9,9,14,56,34,26,20,77,107,107,107,107,114,177,30,30,21,21,
56,113,0,109,109,107,113,113,117,155,147,177,172,177,183,239,217,276,163,240,
240,255,255,270,234,226,242,221,69,64,0,0,-28,0,0,29991,29992] In this example,
Black played a bit more precisely and White didn't have the possibility to
develop an immediate attack. Since Black increased his pressure on the
c3-knight, White employed the typical idea Rh3.} 1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 d6 3. d4 cxd4
4. Qxd4 Nc6 5. Qd2 Nf6 6. b3 e6 7. Bb2 Be7 8. O-O-O O-O 9. f4 d5 10. e5 Nd7 11.
Nf3 Qa5 {[%cal Ge7b4,Gd7c5,Gc5e4] This is probably Black's most ambitious plan.
The idea is to put tremendous pressure on the c3-knight by means of simple
moves such as ...Bb4 followed by the manoeuvre...Nc5-e4. White, however, has
many ways to neutralize the pressure.} 12. Kb1 {When the black queen is
already on a5, we should include this prophylactic move.} Bb4 13. Qd3 {[%cal
Gf3g5,Gh2h4] Immediately introducing the idea Ng5 followed by h2-h4.} ({
The alternative would have been} 13. Qe3 a6 14. h4 {[%csl Bc3][%cal Bf3g5,
Bh1h3] White is ready to proceed with Ng5 and Rh3. From the h3-square, the
rook will participate both in the attack and defence. Black does not have any
targets on the queenside.}) 13... Nc5 14. Qe3 Bd7 15. h4 Rac8 16. Rh3 $6 {
Even though this move is quite typical, White should have played more
energetically.} ({More to the point would have been} 16. h5 {planning h5-h6.
The counterplay is based on} Bxc3 17. Bxc3 Nb4 {is not sufficient since after}
18. Bxb4 Qxb4 19. Rd4 Qb6 20. Bd3 $16 {White manages to prevent Black from
creating any attack on the queenside. At the same time, Black does not have
good ways to stop White's kingside play.}) 16... Ne7 $2 {This is a mistake.} ({
Black should have played} 16... Bxc3 17. Bxc3 Nb4 18. Bxb4 Qxb4 19. Rd4 Qb6
$132 {We get the position that arises in the line with 16.h5, but instead of
the advance h4-h5, White has played Rh3 which is useless. Black has sufficient
counterplay.}) 17. Nd4 Ba3 18. h5 Bxb2 19. Kxb2 {White is strategically
winning since Black does not have any counterplay. Later on, Nihal managed to
win in a convincing way.} b5 20. Bxb5 Bxb5 21. Ncxb5 Ne4 22. Nd6 Rc3 23. Qxc3
Nxc3 24. Rxc3 Qb6 25. g4 Rb8 26. f5 exf5 27. gxf5 f6 28. exf6 Qxd6 29. fxe7 Re8
30. Nc6 h6 31. Rd4 Kh7 32. a4 a6 33. b4 Rc8 34. Kb3 Re8 35. Rc5 Qf6 36. Rdxd5
Qa1 37. Rd8 Qb1+ 38. Kc3 Qe1+ 39. Kb2 Rxe7 40. b5 axb5 41. Rxb5 Rc7 42. Rbb8 g5
43. f6 {1-0 Black resigns.} 1-0

