{[%evp 0,32,26,17,48,35,64,36,41,42,42,32,33,-14,19,19,13,10,4,4,17,22,21,3,17,
0,6,19,18,20,47,54,54,23,54] In the last example featuring the French
structure, White failed to correctly evaluate the potential of his kingside
attack and agreed to a draw in a more promising position.} 1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 d6
3. d4 cxd4 4. Qxd4 Nc6 5. Qd2 Nf6 6. b3 e6 7. Bb2 Be7 8. O-O-O O-O 9. f4 Qa5
10. Nf3 Rd8 11. Qe1 $1 {[%csl Ba5][%cal Bd8d1,Bc3d5,Ba5e1,Be4e5,Be1h4]
Remember this typical multi-purpose move. The queen is very well placed on e1.
When the black queen is not protected, White can always play Nd5. Additionally,
the queen supports the advance e4-e5 and can often be transferred to the
kingside.} d5 12. e5 Ne8 {We have reached our familiar French structure.
Black's counterplay is based on ...Bb4. Later on, he can follow with ...Nc7
followed by ...d5-d4 and possibly ...Nd5.} 13. Kb1 {Never forget this move
when Black has a queen on a5.} Bb4 14. Qe3 Bc5 15. Qd3 {[%csl Bd3][%cal Bf3g5]
The queen finally reached its perfect square. Now, Black should reckon with
the threat of Ng5.} Be7 {[%csl Bg8][%cal Bd5d4,Bc6b4] At this point, being
concerned about ...d5-d4 followed by ...Nb4, Delchev played} 16. Qd2 $6 {
which leads to repetition.} ({White should have played} 16. h4 $1 {[%cal Gf3g5]
with the obvious idea of Ng5.} d4 {Black's most logical continuation.} ({
Note that even after} 16... h6 {White's best move is} 17. Ng5 {You should know
that if White manages to open the h-file, Black will be mated. For example,
after} hxg5 18. hxg5 Bb4 19. g6 {[%cal Gh1h8,Gg6f7,Gd3h3] White's attack is
unstoppable. The idea is to proceed with Rh8+ followed by gxf7 and Qh3 mate.})
17. Ng5 $1 {The c3-knight can way. Delivering checkmate is far more important!}
g6 ({Accepting the sacrifice with} 17... Bxg5 18. hxg5 dxc3 {is losing. After}
19. Qxh7+ Kf8 20. Rxd8 Nxd8 21. Bc1 {[%cal Ga2a4,Gc1a3] Black is going to be
mated. White's idea is a2-a4 followed by Ba3. Black can do nothing to stop
this idea.}) 18. Na4 {[%cal Bb7b5,Bb5a4]} Nb4 19. Qf3 b5 20. h5 $1 {By now, we
already know that sacrificing a piece on the queenside is a common theme in
these positions. The kingside attack is very fast.} bxa4 ({The alternative} 
20... Bxg5 {does not help. After} 21. fxg5 bxa4 22. hxg6 hxg6 23. Bc4 $18 {
[%csl Bb1,Bg8,Ba8][%cal Ba4b3,Bc4b3] White is winning. Playing with a safe
king, White has all the time of the world to bring his pieces to the kingside
and deliver checkmate.}) 21. hxg6 fxg6 22. Rxh7 axb3 {Black's attack is not
dangerous at all. The b2-bishop prevents all mating ideas.} 23. Rh8+ {[%cal
Bf3h3,Bh3h7]} Kg7 24. axb3 Qa2+ 25. Kc1 $18 {[%cal Bf3h3,Bh3h7] with Qh3 to
follow. Black can already resign.}) 16... Bb4 {At this point, opponents agreed
to a draw.} 1/2-1/2

