{[%evp 0,47,20,17,35,45,67,36,35,42,42,24,21,-14,19,13,10,2,8,8,17,-20,-26,-26,
-26,-26,12,23,-7,1,0,0,90,82,94,50,253,279,279,171,1095,1119,1119,1112,1132,
1132,1480,1477,1477,1522] In my opinion, the pure Scheveningen setups is
Black's worst option against the Carlsen Variation. The reason is that White
quickly organizes a kingside attack. In the following examples, we will see
all the important typical attacking ideas.} 1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4.
Qxd4 Nc6 5. Qd2 Nf6 6. b3 e6 7. Bb2 Be7 8. O-O-O a6 {[%cal Bf2f3,Bg2g4,Bh2h4,
Bg4g5]} 9. f4 O-O {This is the most important position in the Scheveningen
setup. Black is planning to proceed with ...b7-b5 followed by ...Bb7 and ...
Rc8. On the other hand, White should organize a kingside attack. In this
position, we need to be very energetic since, after the advance ...b5-b4, the
e4-pawn is getting vulnerable. Therefore, my suggestion is the immediate} 10.
g4 $1 {This is the key move in White's entire concept. White starts his attack
at the price of a pawn sacrifice. In positions with opposite castles, the
material shouldn't be our main concern. The speed of the attack is a far more
important factor. In the beginning, we shall see what happens when Black takes
the pawn with} Nxg4 {Of course, this is a very risky decision. The open g-file
in a combination with the b2-bishop gives White a tremendously strong attack.
The following moves are quite natural -} 11. Nf3 {[%csl Bg1,Bb2][%cal Bh1g1,
Bg1g7]} Nf6 12. Rg1 b5 13. e5 {A typical attacking idea in this setup. Besides
gaining space and freeing the e4-square for his knight, White chases away the
only defender of the black king.} ({The computer insists that starting with} 
13. h4 Bb7 14. h5 {is even more precise. Later, White will play e4-e5 anyway.})
13... Ne8 14. exd6 $2 {This move loses the advantage.} ({In my opinion, the
most precise would have been} 14. Qe3 {[%cal Bc3e4,Bd1d8]} d5 15. f5 {with a
devastating attack. The following variation is a good illustration of what
could happen -} Kh8 16. f6 gxf6 17. Qh6 f5 18. Bd3 {[%csl Bb2][%cal Bd3f5,
Bc3d5,Be5e6,Bd5f6]} Rb8 19. Bxf5 exf5 20. Nxd5 {[%cal Be5e6,Bd5f6]} Be6 21. Nf6
$18 {White is winning.}) ({Another option is} 14. Qg2 d5 15. Qh3 {[%cal Bf1d3,
Bg7g6,Bh3h6,Bh2h4,Bh4h5] with Bd3 to follow. Once Black plays the committing ..
.g7-g6, White will opt for Qh6 followed by h2-h4-h5.}) 14... Qxd6 15. Bd3 Bf6
$4 {This is losing on the spot.} ({Better would have been} 15... f5 {when
White should still prove his advantage.}) 16. Ng5 Bxg5 17. Rxg5 $18 {The
attack is tremendously strong. Black does not have a good defence.} Qe7 18. Qg2
f6 19. Rh5 Qc7 20. Bxh7+ Kf7 21. Bg6+ Ke7 22. Qe4 Qb7 23. Nd5+ Kd8 24. Nxf6+ {
1-0 Black resigns.} 1-0

