701,501,629,554,700,725,761,544,561,583,613,672,731,740,866,863,896,864,985,
886,953,1029,1174,1894,1924,1924] In the last example dedicated to the
Scheveningen setup, we are going to take a look at Black's most precise way of
handling the position.} 1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Qxd4 Nf6 5. b3 Nc6 6.
Qd2 e6 7. Bb2 Be7 8. O-O-O O-O 9. f4 a6 10. g4 b5 {[%csl Re4] Without wasting
time, Black immediately starts expanding on the queenside. His main positional
idea is to combine the pressure on e4 with threats along the semi-open c-file.
If White allows, Black would like to follow with ...Bb7, ... Rc8, ...b5-b5,
and possibly ...Nf6-d7-c5. If White plays correctly, however, his kingside
attack is likely to prevail.} 11. g5 Nd7 {[%csl Be4][%cal Bc8c1,Bc8b7,Ba8c8,
Bb5b4,Bd7c5]} 12. Nf3 {Actually, this natural move is an inaccuracy. The
problem is that now White does not support the e4-pawn.} ({The most precise
continuation would have been} 12. Nge2 {[%csl Be4][%cal Be2g3,Bf4f5,Bg3h5] The
idea is to overprotect the e4-pawn by means of Ng3. Later on, the g3-knight
can even join the attack via h5. Of course, advancing the kingside pawn is the
other thematic idea. My suggestion is the prepare the advance f4-f5-f6. A
possible line would be} Nc5 13. Ng3 b4 {[%cal Ba6a5,Ba5a4]} 14. Na4 $1 {
Once again, we agree to spoil our queenside structure in order to slow down
Black's attack. Otherwise, Black will organize a quick attack by means of ...
a6-a5-a4. The next few moves are quite logical -} Nxa4 15. bxa4 Bb7 16. Kb1 Rc8
17. h4 {[%cal Gf1d3,Gf4f5,Gf5f6] White's attack is very dangerous. After
putting the bishop on d3, he is ready to follow with the advance f4-f5-f6.
After} Qa5 {we don't care for the pawn. The most natural option would be} 18.
Bd3 Qxa4 19. f5 {[%cal Bf5f6] when White's attack is unstoppable. After} Ne5
20. f6 Bd8 21. fxg7 Kxg7 22. Nh5+ Kg8 23. Nf6+ Kg7 24. Ng4 $18 {White is
winning.}) 12... Bb7 13. Bd3 Rc8 {Due to White's slow play, Black obtained
decent counterplay. Nevertheless, after a long fight, the Spanish GM managed
to win.} 14. Kb1 Nb4 15. Rhe1 Nxd3 16. Qxd3 Qc7 17. a3 Rfd8 18. f5 Ne5 19. Nxe5
dxe5 20. Qh3 exf5 21. Qxf5 g6 22. Qg4 b4 23. Rxd8+ Rxd8 24. axb4 Bxb4 25. Re3
Rd2 26. h4 Rf2 27. Qg3 Rf1+ 28. Re1 Rf4 29. Rd1 Bxe4 30. Nxe4 Rxe4 31. Qd3 Qc6
