{[%evp 0,59,23,17,51,51,65,49,49,49,41,13,13,-4,35,36,22,21,14,14,40,16,11,-22,
47,33,27,55,51,53,62,43,55,3,11,11,34,52,76,67,93,89,158,79,210,228,228,163,
172,156,307,309,309,294,362,362,1049,1049,29993,29994,29995,29996] Finally, we
shall deal with the Najdorf setups. As it will become clear, Carlsen Variation
is very well suited to meet the Najdorf style of play. Black can combine the
move ...e7-e5 with ...Nc6 (which reminds the Boleslavsky Variation) or play in
a pure Najdorf style with ...Nbd7. This example shows how to answer the system
with ...Nc6.} 1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Qxd4 {[%csl Bb8][%cal Be7e5]}
Nc6 5. Qd2 Nf6 6. b3 e5 7. Bb2 {[%csl Bc6,Bd7,Be4][%cal Ba7a6,Bb7b5,Bc8b7,
Bd7c5,Ba7a5,Ba2a4,Bc6b4]} Be7 8. O-O-O {This is the first important position
in this line. Black should decide whether to start with ...0-0 or ... Be6. In
my opinion, the move} O-O {is more precise since sooner or later, Black needs
to castle. For the time being, Black postpones his decision regarding the
development of the light-squared bishop.} ({The immediate} 8... Be6 {is
slightly dubious. White can often harass the bishop by means of the advance
f2-f4-f5. At the same time, Black's queenside counterplay turns out to be too
slow. The following variation is a good example of what might happen in this
line -} 9. Kb1 O-O 10. f4 {Against the Najdorf setup, we will always go for
f2-f4. I find the English Attack style starting with f2-f3 to be too slow.} a5
{This is the only way to justify the combination of the moves ...e7-e5 and ...
Nc6. By introducing the threat of ...a5-a4, Black wants to provoke the move
a2-a4. Then, the idea is to start preparing ...d6-d5 by means of ...Nb4 and ...
Rc8. Actually, this is a concept that is borrowed from the Boleslavsky
variation.} 11. f5 {This move is one of the major drawbacks of the early ...
Be6. After} Bd7 {White can speed up his attack with the thematic pawn sacrifice
} 12. g4 $5 {[%cal Gg4g5] White's attack is very fast.} a4 ({Taking the pawn
results in a position that is lost for Black -} 12... Nxg4 13. Nf3 Nf6 14. Rg1
Kh8 15. Bc4 $18 {[%cal Bf3g5,Bd2e3,Be3h3] Black is helpless. In the next few
moves, White is going to deliver checkmate. A possible way of finishing Black
off would be Ng5 followed by Qe3-h3. White is even not in a hurry since Black
does not have any counterplay at all.}) 13. g5 Nxe4 14. Nxe4 Bxf5 15. Bd3 $16 {
Black does not have enough compensation for the piece.}) 9. Kb1 a5 10. a4 {
[%csl Bb4]} Nb4 {[%csl Bf6,Bb4][%cal Bd6d5,Be4d5,Bc8f5,Ba8c8] Black is
preparing the advance ...d6-d5. The idea is to answer exd5 with ...Bf5. We can
now see the point behind keeping the bishop on c8. In the game, White missed
Black's idea and played the careless} 11. f4 $6 ({The best would have been} 11.
Bd3 $1 {anticipating the appearance of the black bishop on f5. Now, it's very
difficult for Black to create any counterplay. White's next move is going to
be f2-f4.} Be6 ({The advance} 11... d5 {is now well met by} 12. exd5 Nfxd5 13.
Nf3 $16 {[%csl Be5][%cal Bc3d5,Bb4d5] when Black's lack of development does
not allow him to stabilize the overextended position.}) 12. f4 Rc8 13. Nf3 Nxd3
14. Qxd3 {Black should already reckon with f4-f5 followed by g2-g4. Therefore,
the best seems to be} exf4 15. h3 {[%csl Bf4][%cal Bf6g4,Bh1e1,Bc3b5] Before
starting active actions, White takes the g4-square under control. Then he can
make use of Black's weaknesses by means of simple moves such as Rhe1 followed
by Nb5.} Nd7 16. Rhe1 Bf6 17. Nb5 Bxb2 18. Kxb2 Qf6+ 19. Qd4 $16 {White has an
obvious advantage. Black cannot hold all his weaknesses.}) ({In his book,
Coffeehouse Repertoire 1.e4 (Volume 1), GM Gawain Jones suggests} 11. Nf3 $5 {
[%cal Bf1c4,Bd2e2,Bd1d2,Bh1d1] followed by Bc4.} Qc7 ({White's idea is to
answer} 11... Be6 {with} 12. Ng5) 12. Bc4 Be6 13. Bxe6 fxe6 14. Qe2 $14 {
White has stable advantage in view of his better pawn structure.}) 11... Be6 $6
{Black does not take his chance.} ({The best would have been} 11... d5 $1 12.
fxe5 Nxe4 13. Nxe4 Bf5 ({Another option is} 13... dxe4 14. Qxd8 Rxd8 15. Rxd8+
Bxd8 $132) 14. Nc3 Bxc2+ 15. Qxc2 Nxc2 16. Kxc2 $13 {The position is very
unclear.}) 12. Nf3 exf4 13. Nd4 Rc8 14. Qxf4 Rc5 15. Bd3 Nd7 16. Nd5 (16. Ncb5
$16) 16... Bxd5 17. exd5 Ne5 18. Be4 Bf6 19. Nf5 Re8 20. Rhf1 Qc7 21. Rf2 b5
22. axb5 Rxb5 23. Qg3 a4 24. Nd4 Ra5 25. Rxf6 axb3 26. Nxb3 Ra2 27. Rd4 Nc4 28.
Bxh7+ Kxh7 29. Rh4+ Kg8 30. Rh8+ {1-0 Black resigns.} 1-0

