{[%evp 0,43,30,15,48,48,57,49,41,45,56,2,27,27,22,10,13,14,0,16,16,4,4,6,56,42,
42,42,48,24,16,3,23,15,35,15,15,45,45,20,40,35,35,43,29,24] Finally, we shall
take a look at Black's most challenging setup - Najdorf with ...Nbd7. Since
the d7-knight does not close the diagonal h1-a8, Black can put more pressure
on e4 by means of ...b7-b5 followed by ...Bb7. Nevertheless, I think that my
suggested setup would create at least practical problems for Black.} 1. e4 c5
2. Nc3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Qxd4 Nf6 5. b3 e5 {[%csl Bb8]} 6. Qd2 Be7 ({Black can
also start with} 6... Nbd7 {when most probably there will be a transposition.})
7. Bb2 O-O 8. O-O-O a6 9. Kb1 b5 {[%csl Be4][%cal Bc8b7,Bb8d7] Black's idea
becomes clear. He is going to play ...Nbd7 and ...Bb7, thus putting pressure
on e4. Therefore, White does not have enough time to develop his typical
kingside attack. At this point, my suggestion would be} 10. Nge2 {[%csl Bg3]
[%cal Be2g3,Bb5b4,Bc3d5,Bf2f4,Bg3f5,Bh2h4,Bh4h5,Bh5h6] Just like in the
previous line, White is going to defend the e4-pawn via the g3-square.
Afterwards, if possible, we try to carry out the advance f2-f4. Note that the
move ...b5-b4 should be met by Nd5. Once White manages to secure the central
stability, he can consider active actions on the kingside. In many cases, the
advance of the h-pawn is also an option to consider.} ({I don't like the
English Attack setup based on} 10. f3 {The problem is that after} b4 11. Nd5
Nxd5 12. Qxd5 (12. exd5 a5 $132) 12... Qb6 {[%cal Gc8b7,Gb8d7,Ga6a5,Ga5a4]
Black gets enough counterplay. His next moves will be ...Bb7 followed by ...
Nd7 and ...a5-a4.}) 10... Nbd7 {The most flexible continuation.} ({Less
precise is} 10... b4 11. Nd5 Nxe4 12. Qe3 {when White's superior piece
activity, as well as the better development, provide more than enough
compensation for the pawn. A possible line would be} Nf6 13. Nef4 Bb7 14. Nxf6+
Bxf6 15. Nh5 {[%cal Bf1c4,Bf2f4] White is ready to follow with Bc4 and f2-f4.
Black is under tremendous pressure.}) 11. Ng3 b4 {Sooner or later, Black
should play this move.} ({An alternative is} 11... Bb7 {when my suggestion
would be} 12. h4 {[%cal Gh4h5,Gh5h6] By advancing the pawn all the way to h6,
White wants to create kingside weaknesses.} b4 13. Nd5 Nxd5 14. exd5 a5 15. f4
f6 16. Nf5 $40 {with a dangerous attack.}) 12. Nd5 {[%csl Bb4][%cal Bd5e7,
Bd2d6]} Nxd5 13. Qxd5 {It turns out that Black has problems due to his
overextended queenside. In many cases, the e4-pawn can be vulnerable.
Additionally, it's important that the white bishop has access to the c4-square.
} Ra7 ({After} 13... Nb6 $6 14. Qa5 Qc7 15. Qxb4 {Black does not have
compensation for the pawn.}) 14. f4 Qc7 ({Another direction is} 14... a5 {
when White should play} 15. Qd2 {[%cal Gf1c4] planning to develop the bishop
via c4. A possible line would be} Qb6 16. Bc4 a4 17. Nf5 Nc5 18. fxe5 dxe5 19.
Qe3 Bxf5 20. exf5 axb3 21. Bxb3 $14 {White keeps a slight edge in this
position.}) ({A blunder would be} 14... exf4 $4 {in view of} 15. Qd4 {[%cal
Bd4a7,Bd4g7] when White is winning on the spot.}) 15. Qd2 {White follows the
same strategy. He is planning to proceed with Bc4 and Nf5. The following line
illustrates the character of the play.} a5 16. Nf5 Nc5 17. Bc4 $1 {This
typical move is good even when it is connected with a pawn sacrifice. In this
concrete case, White can even regain the pawn by force.} Nxe4 18. Nxe7+ Qxe7
19. Qe3 Nc3+ 20. Bxc3 bxc3 21. fxe5 dxe5 22. Rhe1 $14 {After regaining the
pawn, White will enjoy a nice initiative in view of his more active pieces.} *

