{[%evp 0,63,28,25,60,58,77,42,42,42,62,4,3,0,-12,6,17,18,8,-39,5,-32,-5,-6,41,
29,161,175,180,163,163,160,217,186,189,157,142,117,117,124,170,177,321,198,198,
238,212,212,225,185,200,156,294,231,271,199,229,217,432,438,447,450,451,456,
464,489] I would like to start with a game played by my student Jeffery Xiong.
Since in 2018, this variation wasn't that popular, Jeffery wasn't well
prepared for it. Therefore, he played on general grounds and quickly found
himself in trouble.} 1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Qxd4 Bd7 {Of course,
this rare move is dubious. Psychologically, we can explain that Black rejected
the immediate 4...Nc6 because of Bb5. The nature of the position, however,
remains unchanged.} 5. b3 Nc6 6. Qd2 g6 7. Bb2 Bg7 8. O-O-O Nf6 9. f3 O-O {
This version of Dragon is quite favorable for White. Instead of being on e3,
White has a bishop on b2. Therefore, the White king is completely safe now.
Instead of exchanging the dark-squared bishops via h6 (as in the classical
Dragon), White can carry out the exchange by means of Nd5. At this point,
Sevian played} 10. g4 {which is the most precise continuation. I always prefer
to start with g2-g4 to prevent the advance ...h7-h5, which would slow down
White's attack.} ({Another instructive game saw} 10. h4 Rc8 ({Of course, Black
should have played} 10... h5 {slowing down White's attack.}) 11. Kb1 ({Once
again,} 11. g4 {would have been better.}) 11... Qa5 12. g4 Rc7 13. Nge2 b5 14.
Nf4 {[%cal Gc3d5] In this structure, f4-square is the perfect spot for our
knight. From this position, the knight supports the advance h4-h5 and makes
possible the idea Ncd5.} Rfc8 15. g5 Ne8 16. Ncd5 Qxd2 17. Rxd2 {Even after
the exchange of the queens, White's attack keeps going.} Rb7 18. h5 e6 19. Bxg7
Kxg7 20. hxg6 fxg6 21. Rdh2 {White was already winning. Kashlinskaya managed
to win in a few moves.} exd5 22. Rxh7+ Kg8 23. Nxd5 Ng7 24. Nf6+ Kf7 25. Rxg7+
Kxg7 26. Rh7+ Kf8 27. Nxd7+ Rxd7 28. Rxd7 Nd4 29. Rxd6 Nxc2 30. Kb2 b4 31. Bc4
{1-0 (31) Kashlinskaya,A (2435)-Wagner,A (2313) Dortmund 2018}) 10... a5 {
Obviously, Black is planning to follow with ...a5-a4. Unfortunately for him,
however, the queenside attack is prolonged.} ({Probably, a bit more flexible
would have been} 10... Qa5 $5 11. Kb1 Rfd8 {playing for ... d6-d5.}) 11. Kb1 ({
The move} 11. Bb5 {allows Black to create some counterplay with} a4 12. Bxa4
Qa5 $132) ({Another possibility is} 11. a4 {when Black's idea is} Nb4 {Even in
this case, White's attack is faster.}) 11... a4 $6 {In my opinion, this is
premature.} (11... Qb6 $142 {More precise would have been} 12. h4 a4 {with
decent counter chances.}) 12. Nxa4 Rxa4 {Unfortunately, this typical exchange
sacrifice does not give Black enough compensation.} 13. bxa4 Qb6 14. Bb5 {
[%cal Gc2c4] White wants to fortify the queenside with c2-c4.} Ra8 15. c4 Ne8
16. Ne2 Ne5 17. Bd4 Qc7 18. Qc3 {White is winning due to his extra exchange
and safe king.} Bxb5 19. axb5 Nxc4 20. Bxg7 Qc5 21. Rd5 Na3+ 22. Ka1 Qf2 23.
Rd2 Nxg7 24. Nd4 Qh4 25. Rc1 h5 26. gxh5 Nxh5 27. Rb2 Kh7 28. Rb3 Qf2 29. Qb2
Qxb2+ 30. Kxb2 Ra4 31. Rxa3 Rxd4 32. Rc7 1-0

