{[%evp 0,82,28,30,46,52,85,66,58,49,49,27,24,-9,-1,-1,11,-8,0,10,5,-4,39,39,31,
-13,2,11,7,1,1,12,7,20,12,8,19,-16,12,8,17,1,-1,-18,18,6,0,7,-7,-4,21,20,29,33,
31,19,26,24,24,22,21,8,60,21,61,40,46,46,46,35,46,33,46,31,31,35,31,31,31,31,
31,31,32,32,31]} 1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Qxd4 Nc6 {This is the right
move order if Black wants to play a Dragon setup.} 5. Qd2 g6 6. b3 {At this
point, the most challenging continuation is ...Bh6. Nevertheless, in order to
understand all the typical ideas, we should start with} Bg7 {which was the
choice of MVL in this game.} 7. Bb2 Nf6 8. O-O-O O-O 9. Kb1 {I am not sure
about this overcautious move. As we are going to see later, Hikaru was in a
mood to play it safe.} ({An alternative would be} 9. f3 {[%cal Gg2g4]
intending to proceed with the immediate g2-g4.} Qa5 10. Kb1 {When the black
queen is already on a5, this prophylactic move is justified.} ({Another
possibility is} 10. g4 $5 {Nevertheless, after} d5 11. exd5 Rd8 12. g5 Ne8 $44
{Black has decent counterplay.}) 10... Be6 ({Another GM game saw} 10... a6 11.
h4 {In my opinion, the immediate g2-g4 would have been better.} h5 12. Nge2 b5
{[#]} 13. g4 $3 {The most typical way to attack in a Dragon type of structure.}
hxg4 14. h5 $3 {White is already winning. In positions with castles on
opposite wings, our only idea is to be quicker than the opponent. It's like a
race. Therefore, the material shouldn't be our main concern.} Nxh5 15. Rxh5 {
Another thematic sacrifice. The idea is to destroy the shelter of the black
king.} gxh5 16. Ng3 h4 17. Nh5 f6 18. Qd5+ Kh8 19. Qxc6 $18 {White is already
winning.} Be6 20. Nd5 Rac8 21. Qb7 Rfe8 22. Nxg7 Kxg7 23. Nxf6 Kf7 24. Nxe8
Kxe8 25. fxg4 Rc7 26. Qa8+ Rc8 27. Qa7 b4 28. Qxa6 Qc5 29. Qb5+ {1-0 (29)
Maghsoodloo,P (2698)-Pour Agha Bala,A (2432) Europe Echecs INT 2021}) ({
Of course, a logical setup will be} 10... Rd8 11. Nge2 e5 {when we have a
position that is similar to the game Nakamura - Vachier Lagrave.}) (10... h5 $1
{I like most this idea. Anyway, Black should play this move sooner or later.})
11. Nge2 Rac8 12. Nf4 {As usual, the knight is heading for f4. When Black has
played ...Be6, this move is even more effective. Black should now reckon with
the idea of Nxe6 followed by Bc4.} Bh6 13. g3 Nh5 14. Bb5 Rfe8 15. a3 a6 16.
Be2 Bd7 17. Rhg1 {White anticipates the eventual exchange on f4 that will
happen sooner or later.} Ne5 18. Ncd5 $1 {Forcing the transition into a
favorable endgame. It's important to understand that due to the control of the
d5-square, White is almost always better in Dragon endgames.} Qxd2 19. Rxd2 Bc6
20. Rdd1 Nxf4 21. gxf4 Nd7 22. f5 {White's advantage is obvious. Later on,
Kotronias managed to convert.} Bg7 23. Bc1 Nf6 24. fxg6 hxg6 25. c4 Bxd5 26.
exd5 Nd7 27. f4 Nc5 28. f5 Nxb3 29. fxg6 f5 30. Bd3 Nxc1 31. Rxc1 Rf8 32. Rcf1
f4 33. Rf3 Bh6 34. Re1 Rc7 35. h4 Kg7 36. a4 a5 37. Ka2 Rd8 38. Rf2 Kh8 39.
Rfe2 Re8 40. Re6 f3 41. Rf6 exf6 42. Rxe8+ Kg7 43. Kb3 f2 44. h5 Bg5 45. Kc2 f5
46. Kd1 Re7 47. Rxe7+ Bxe7 48. c5 dxc5 49. Ke2 Kf6 50. Bxf5 Bf8 51. d6 c4 52.
Kxf2 b5 53. d7 {1-0 (53) Kotronias,V (2509)-Grinberg,E (2452) Budapest 2018})
9... Qa5 10. Nge2 e5 $5 {I like that idea. Black wants to restrict the
e2-knight as well as the b2-bishop. In the future, he will be trying to carry
out the advance ...d6-d5.} 11. f3 Rd8 12. Nd5 {Very safe approach but not
connected with the dynamic of the position.} ({Better would be} 12. g4 $1 {
which is an improvement over the game of Nakamura.} Be6 13. g5 Nh5 14. h4 {
[%cal Gc3d5] Besides the usual Nd5, White is getting ready to exchange the
light-squared bishops via h3.} Qb6 15. Nd5 Qf2 16. Bh3 Qxf3 17. Bxe6 fxe6 18.
Nc7 Rac8 19. Nxe6 Re8 20. Rhf1 Qg4 21. Nxg7 Kxg7 22. Qe3 $16 {White has an
obvious advantage because of his active pieces and safer king.} Rf8 23. Rg1
Qxh4 24. Rxd6 Rcd8 25. Rd5 Kg8 26. Rgd1 Rde8 27. Nc1 Qf4 28. Qc5 Qxe4 29. Rd7
Rf7 30. Rxf7 Kxf7 31. Rd7+ Kg8 32. Rxb7 Nf4 33. Rc7 Nd8 34. Qxa7 Nde6 35. Rxh7
Rf8 36. Ba3 Rf5 37. Rb7 {1-0 (37) Popov,I (2604)-Kovacevic,A (2480) Subotica
2019}) 12... Qxd2 13. Nxf6+ Bxf6 14. Rxd2 Bg5 15. Rd1 Be6 {Black managed to
solve his opening problems. White's very tiny edge is not enough to win the
game.} 16. Nc3 Nd4 17. Bd3 Rac8 18. Rhf1 Nc6 19. a3 Ne7 20. Ne2 Be3 21. h3 g5
22. a4 f6 23. c4 Ng6 24. Bc1 Bxc1 25. Nxc1 h5 26. Rf2 h4 27. Rfd2 Kf7 28. Ne2
Ke7 29. Kb2 Nf4 30. Nc3 a5 31. Bf1 b6 32. Bd3 Rc5 33. Bc2 Rc7 34. Re1 Rc5 35.
Nd1 Rc6 36. Ne3 Rc7 37. Red1 Rc6 38. Bd3 Rc7 39. Bc2 Rc6 40. Bd3 Rc7 41. Bc2
Rc6 1/2-1/2

