1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Qxd4 Nc6 5. Qd2 g6 6. b3 Bh6 $1 {This is the
modern way to handle the position for Black, and I believe the best try. Black
wins a tempo for developing his pieces.} 7. f4 {This move is practically
forced, now Black's main idea is connected with the advance e7-e5, but he
should be cautious} Nf6 (7... e5 $2 {This is wrong now} 8. Nb5 $1 Bxf4 9. Qxd6
Qxd6 10. Nxd6+ Ke7 11. Ba3 $18 {1-0 (40) Maghsoodloo,P (2674)-Preotu,R (2494)
Chess.com INT 2020}) 8. Bb2 e5 (8... O-O 9. O-O-O a5 {I'm not too fond of this
setup. Black doesn't have counterplay} 10. a4 Nb4 11. Kb1 d5 {I think is a
wrong decision. The setup with Bh6 is connected with e5, not with d5} 12. e5
Nh5 $2 {The knight on the edge of the board looks weird} (12... Ne4 $3 {
is the best decision} 13. Nxe4 Bf5 $1 {this is what Black probably missed}) 13.
Nge2 Bf5 14. Nd4 Bg4 15. Be2 (15. g3 $1 {this exchange sacrifice looks very
strong}) 15... Bxf4 16. Qe1 Bxe2 17. Qxe2 Qc7 18. Rde1 {Black won a pawn, but
White's position is much better. The knight on "h5" is very poor. White can
easily organize an attack against Black's king.} Qc5 19. Ncb5 Rac8 20. Rhf1 Bh6
21. c3 Nc6 22. Nf5 $3 $18 {Now the game is practically over} gxf5 23. Qxh5 Bg7
24. Rxf5 Qb6 25. Rg5 Nd8 26. Bc1 Qf2 27. Re3 Ne6 28. Reg3 Qe1 29. R5g4 Rfd8 30.
Re3 Qg1 31. Rh3 Nf8 32. e6 fxe6 33. Qh6 {1-0 (33) Dubov,D (2691) -Firouzja,A 
(2561) Abu Dhabi 2018}) 9. Nge2 {Grischuk chooses to develop the piece than to
lose time for g3.} (9. g3 {is a bit slow here. I prefer Grischuk's approach}
O-O 10. O-O-O exf4 (10... Re8 11. Kb1 Nd4 12. Nge2 Bg4 13. Nxd4 exd4 14. Qxd4
Bg7 {Black has enough compensation for the pawn 1/2 (23)-1/ 2 (23) Paichadze,L
(2564) -Donchenko,A (2657) Reykjavik 2021}) 11. gxf4 Nh5 $13 {0-1 (35) Kovalev,
V (2637)-Fedoseev,V (2696) Krasnaya Polyana 2021}) (9. Nb5 $4 Nxe4 $1 $19) 9...
O-O 10. O-O-O Be6 11. Kb1 a5 12. a4 Qb6 13. h4 $1 {again and again this idea.
Now we can see one of the drawbacks of the bishop placed on "h6". Black can't
play h7-h5} Rac8 14. h5 $1 {Very similar to the Dragon} Nxh5 15. g3 $1 {
The idea is to exchange the bishops by means of Bh3, followed by doubling the
rooks on the h-file} (15. Rxh5 $2 {is not working here. White's pieces are
quite far from the kingside} gxh5) 15... Nb4 16. Bh3 Bxh3 17. Rxh3 Bg7 18. g4
Nf6 19. g5 Nh5 20. f5 $18 {it is already over, and Grischuk won it after some
complications in the time trouble} Rfd8 21. f6 Bf8 22. Ng3 d5 23. exd5 Nxg3 24.
Rxg3 h5 25. Qe2 Rc5 26. Rh3 Nxd5 27. Nxd5 Rcxd5 28. Rdh1 Qd6 29. Ka2 Rd1 30.
Rxh5 gxh5 31. Rxh5 Rd4 32. Rh1 Rxa4+ 33. Kb1 Qd5 34. Qh5 Qxh1+ 35. Qxh1 Rg4 36.
Bxe5 Rxg5 37. Qxb7 Rd2 38. Bc3 Re2 39. Qc8 Rg1+ 40. Kb2 Rgg2 41. Bxa5 Rxc2+ 42.
Qxc2 Rxc2+ 43. Kxc2 Kh7 44. Kd3 Kg6 45. Bc3 Kf5 46. Kc4 Ke6 47. b4 Bd6 48. b5 {
I like a lot the idea of 15.g3. I believe this was Grischuk's preparation
which MVL underestimated. I think Black shouldn't go fo opposite castling in
this variation, because White's position is easier to play.} 1-0

