{[%evp 0,23,18,18,48,48,42,17,12,13,41,-4,6,8,41,34,54,7,-8,-18,-5,-7,-7,-14,
20,10]} 1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 e6 3. d4 $5 {This creative approach is recently
getting popular in the high-level practice. Nowadays, when strong engines make
it very difficult to fight for an advantage in the mainstream lines, having
such surprising weapons is a must for every chess player. The idea of these
rare lines is not to refute the opening concept of the opponent. They are
designed to create practical problems. I believe that the line starting with 3.
d4!? is just a perfect practical choice.} cxd4 {This is, of course, Black's
main move.} ({The alternative} 3... d5 $2 {does not work well -} 4. exd5 exd5
5. dxc5 {It turns out that it's not so easy for Black to regain the pawn due
to the vulnerable d5-pawn.} ({Another possible option is} 5. Bb5+ $5) 5... d4 (
{After} 5... Bxc5 6. Bb5+ Bd7 7. Qxd5 Qe7+ 8. Qe4 Qxe4+ 9. Nxe4 Bxb5 10. Nxc5
$16 {Black does not have any compensation for the pawn.}) ({Too passive is} 
5... Nf6 {when after} 6. Be3 Nc6 7. Bb5 Be7 8. Nge2 O-O 9. h3 $16 {White
enjoys a healthy extra pawn.}) 6. Bb5+ Nc6 7. Qe2+ Be6 8. Ne4 {[%csl Gb5] We
can now see the point behind 7.Qe2+. Since the b5-bishop is now protected,
Black cannot win a piece by means of ...Qa5+.} Nf6 9. Bg5 Be7 10. Bxf6 Bxf6 11.
Nd6+ Kf8 12. Nf3 Qa5+ 13. Qd2 Qxd2+ 14. Kxd2 $16 {Black does not have any
compensation for the pawn.}) 4. Qxd4 Nc6 {This is by far the most challenging
