{[%evp 0,23,18,18,48,48,42,17,12,13,41,-4,6,8,41,34,54,7,-8,-18,-5,-7,-7,-14,
20,10]} 1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 e6 3. d4 $5 cxd4 4. Qxd4 Nc6 5. Qe3 {This will be my
main recommendation. In most of the cases, White will proceed with Bd2
followed by 0-0-0. Nevertheless, in most cases, he keeps a high degree of
flexibility. In this chapter, we are going to examine Black's main deviations
from the main line with 5...Nf6 - 5...a6 and 5...d6.} a6 {After this move,
White has a variety of playable options.} ({The Scheveningen setup starting
with} 5... d6 {always gives White a lot of possibilities. One of the the
promising directions is} 6. Bd2 Nf6 7. O-O-O Be7 8. Qg3 $146 O-O 9. Bh6 Ne8 10.
Nf3 $14 {White's play is easier. For example, after} Kh8 11. Bf4 $14 {White
will combine his kingside play with pressure on d6.}) 6. Bd2 {This move fits
very well into White's concept.} ({After} 6. Qg3 b5 7. Bg5 {, we transpose to
the system with 5.Qd3.}) ({Another decent option is} 6. b3 $5 {trying to
obtain a favourable version of the Carlsen Variation. Having the queen on e3
will be very useful if Black opts for a passive setup based on ... d7-d6.} Be7
{This is the most precise move. Black prepares the immediate ... d7-d5.} ({
Black can easily find himself in a difficult position if he just keeps playing
on general grounds. A typical example is} 6... b5 7. Bb2 Bb7 8. O-O-O Qc7 9.
Nd5 $1 {Remember this typical idea. We can now see the point of having the
queen on e3.} Qa5 10. Kb1 {[%cal Gb2g7]} f6 {This position was reached in the
game 0-1 (32) Tejedor Fuente,E (2434)-Mazi,L (2340) Chess.com INT 2021. Now,
White could have played} 11. Nb6 Rd8 12. Nh3 $16 {with a huge advantage. Black
has problems completing the development.}) 7. Bb2 d5 $1 8. exd5 exd5 {This is
the critical position. Now, White should go for the following sequence -} 9.
Nxd5 ({After} 9. O-O-O Nf6 10. Nge2 O-O 11. f3 Re8 $132 {Black has decent
counterplay due to the exposed position of the queen. The position, however,
remains playable.}) 9... Qxd5 10. Bxg7 Nb4 $1 11. Rc1 Bf5 12. Nf3 Nxc2+ 13.
Rxc2 Bxc2 14. Be2 Qe4 15. Bxh8 Bb4+ 16. Kf1 Rc8 $44 {After a bunch of computer
moves, we reach a roughly balanced position.}) 6... b5 {In practice, this move
has brought good results for Black.} ({As usual. we can answer} 6... Qc7 {with}
7. Qg3 $146 Qxg3 ({White is always happy to face the passive} 7... d6 {A
promising setup would be} 8. f4 b5 9. Bd3 Nf6 10. Nf3 $14 {[%cal Ge4e5] After
having mobilized his pieces, White is ready for the thematic e4-e5 advance.})
8. hxg3 $14 {[%csl Gh7][%cal Gf2f3,Gg3g4] with a typical advantage. After
castling long, White can consider gaining kingside space with f2-f3 followed
by g3-g4.}) 7. Nf3 $5 $146 {This natural move turns out to be a novelty.} ({
Less precise is} 7. O-O-O {since after} Bb7 8. f4 Rc8 $1 $146 ({Less clear is} 
8... b4 9. Nd5 Qa5 10. Kb1 $13 {with mutual chances. 0-1 (52) Sadhwani,R (2545)
-Oleksienko,M (2585) Chess.com INT 2020}) 9. Kb1 Na5 $132 {Black can quickly
develop his queenside play.}) 7... Bb7 8. a4 $5 {When Black is underdeveloped,
White should always consider undermining the queenside with this move.} b4 9.
Nd5 {The position remains complicated but White's play is easier.} *

