an endgame.} ({In the game, Black played} 10... Nxd5 $6 11. Bb2 Bb4 12. c3 Ba5
{1-0 (88) Demchenko, A (2600)-Zakhartsov, V (2499) Novorossiysk 2021 At this
point, White should have played} 13. Bd3 O-O 14. O-O $14 {[%cal Gd2c2,Ga1d1]
when White keeps the advantage due to his better coordination.}) 11. Qxd5 ({
Avoiding the exchange of the queens with} 11. Bd3 {can be answered with} Ne4 {
[%cal Gd5a5] when there is no good retreat for the queen in view of ...Qa5+.})
11... Nxd5 12. Bb5+ Kd8 $13 {The position is unclear.}) 9... Bd7 10. Qe2 Nbxd5
11. Nxd5 Nxd5 12. Bd2 Bd6 13. Bxd7+ Qxd7 14. O-O O-O 15. c4 $14 {Even though
this structure is completely playable for Black, White's play remains easier
due to his better-coordinated pieces.}) 9. Nxd5 Qxd5 10. Bc4 Qc5 {This
position occurred in the game 0-1 (49) Aronian, L (2773)-Carlsen, M (2863)
chess24. com INT 2020. Now, White should have opted for} 11. Qe4 Na5 12. Be3
Qc6 13. Qxc6+ Nxc6 14. O-O-O Ba3+ 15. Kb1 $14 {[%csl Gc8] when White retains a
slight edge. It's not easy for Black to develop the light-squared bishop.}) ({
We should always pay attention to} 6... d5 {White's most promising option
seems to be} 7. exd5 Nxd5 8. Nxd5 Qxd5 9. Bd3 {In this open position, White is
fighting for initiative due to his more active pieces.} Nb4 ({The alternative
is} 9... Bc5 10. Qe2 O-O 11. c3 Bd6 12. Be4 Qh5 13. Be3 {White plays in the
most solid way.} ({Even more promising would be} 13. g4 $5 {with the idea to
answer} Qxg4 {with} 14. Bxh7+) 13... f5 14. Bxc6 bxc6 15. O-O-O Bc7 16. Qc4 $18
{White was already winning in the game (71) Ganguly,S (2635)-Bilguun,S (2454)
Chess. com INT 2020}) 10. Be4 f5 $6 {This move forces the transition into an
endgame that is obviously better for White. 0-1 (39) Shevchenko, K (2633)
-Volokitin,A (2652) Kiev 2021} ({Better would have been} 10... Qc4 $5 11. c3
Nd5 12. Qd4 Qxd4 13. Nxd4 {[%csl Ge4,Gc8] White is still slightly better since
Black has problems developing his light-squared bishop. Additionally, the
queenside pawn majority allows the creation of an outside passed pawn in the
endgame. A possible follow-up would be} Bc5 14. Nb3 Bb6 15. O-O O-O 16. a4 $14
{White keeps an edge.}) 11. Bxd5 Nxc2+ 12. Kd1 Nxe3+ 13. Bxe3 exd5 14. Re1 $36
{[%csl Ge8]}) ({After} 6... Be7 7. e5 Nd5 8. Nxd5 exd5 9. Bd3 $14 {White has a
stable advantage.}) 7. Bd2 {The most principled choice.} ({The immediate} 7. a3
{is well met by} Ng4 $5 $146 {which turns out to be a novelty.} ({White can
rely on a slight advantage after} 7... Bxc3+ 8. Qxc3 d6 {This position was
reached in the game 1/2-1/2 (35) Wachinger, N (2374)-Suvorov, A (2333)
Willingen 2021} ({The alternative} 8... O-O {occurred in 1-0 (27) Schreiter,T 
(1465) -Ventimiglia,C (1925) IECG email 2003 The simplest would have been} 9.
Bd3 d5 10. exd5 Nxd5 11. Qc5 $14 {with a slight advantage due to the bishop
pair and the superior activity.}) {At this point, White could have played} 9.
Nd4 $146 Nxd4 10. Qxd4 O-O 11. Bd3 e5 12. Qe3 $14 {with a slight advantage.})
8. Qf4 Bxc3+ 9. bxc3 Qf6 10. Qxf6 Nxf6 11. Bd3 e5 {The most precise reaction.
Black is ready for the advance ...d7-d5.} ({After} 11... d6 12. a4 e5 13. Ba3
Ke7 14. O-O-O $14 {White manages to put an annoying pressure.}) 12. a4 d5 13.
exd5 Nxd5 14. Bc4 Be6 15. Ng5 Na5 $11 {with equality.}) 7... d6 ({After} 7...
O-O {my suggestion would be} 8. a3 $146 {when after} Ba5 9. e5 Bxc3 10. Qxc3
Ne4 11. Qe3 Nxd2 12. Qxd2 f6 13. exf6 Qxf6 14. O-O-O $14 {White lead in
development promises him a slight advantage.}) 8. O-O-O O-O 9. Bd3 e5 (9... Bc5
10. Qe2 e5 11. Bg5 $14) 10. h3 Be6 11. Kb1 a6 12. Ng5 $13 {With a complex
position} *

