{[%evp 0,11,22,8,44,52,44,52,53,7,0,-5,26,23]} 1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 (2. f4 {Not the
best move order because it allows 2...d5} Nc6 3. Bb5 e6 4. Bxc6 bxc6 5. d3 d5
6. c4 {White's dream structure: Black does not have any counterplay and the
Bc8 is heavily restricted} dxc4 7. dxc4 Qxd1+ 8. Kxd1 {The queen trade does
not help Black at all- the c5 pawn will soon become a target for White's minor
pieces} Nf6 9. Nc3 Nd7 10. Be3 Be7 11. Na4 Ba6 12. b3 O-O 13. Nf3 f6 14. Kc2
Rfd8 15. Ne1 Rac8 16. Nd3 {Losing the pawn is not Black's biggest problem: he
still lacks squares for his pieces} Rc7 17. Ndxc5 Nxc5 18. Bxc5 {There is no
point in going into an endgame with opposite-colored bishops after Nxc5}) 2...
Nc6 3. Bb5 d6 (3... e6 4. Bxc6 {White follows a similar strategy, building
pressure on the center/kingside after either capture} bxc6 {Probably, the
better option as in some cases Black can push d5 and get a decent position} 5.
f4 d6 6. d3 Nf6 ({By comparison with 5.Nf3, here 5...e5 is simply not possible.
Black cannot afford to break his structure after fxe5, dxe5} 6... e5) 7. Nf3
Be7 8. O-O O-O {Black's position is unpleasant because his light-squared
bishop has no prospects of coming into play} 9. Bd2 Nd7 (9... d5 {After d5,
White NEVER takes exd5. Instead, pushing e5 or simply keeping the tension is
equally good. Additionally, White would like to put a pawn on c4 as Black will
never be able to free himself from the doubled c-pawns.}) 10. Kh1 e5 11. f5) 4.
Bxc6+ {Generally in the Sicilian after f4, the battle revolves around the
central e5 square. Therefore, the exchange Bxc6, removing the knight
controlling e5, is in line with White's plan} bxc6 {White needs to push f4 and
can do so either directly or after d3 first} 5. f4 (5. d3) (5. Nf3 {A most
natural move that is actually a positional mistake! Black plays e5 and is
doing great - White simply does not have any pawn breaks!} e5 6. d3 Ne7 {
A deep positional move- the knight comes to Ng6 and stops White's main idea of
f4} 7. a3 {White desperately needs to find active counterplay, but it is not
easy!} a5 8. O-O Ng6 9. Bd2 Be7 10. h3 O-O {Black is ready to start a kingside
offensive with f5. For example,} 11. Qe2 f5 12. Nd1 f4 13. Re1 Nh8 {[%cal
Yg7g5] Black is ready to march his pawns against the enemy king; White is
defenseless}) 5... e5 6. fxe5 *

