{A very instructive game that shows some of the typical plans and ideas in the
structure. The opening line may be different, but White's middlegame play is
the same.} 1. e4 e6 2. Nf3 c5 3. Nc3 Nc6 4. Bb5 d6 5. Bxc6+ bxc6 6. O-O {
White is not very successful in the opening battle as he failed to include f4}
Qc7 (6... e5 {is the way to go}) 7. d3 g6 $6 (7... e5 $1 {There is no stopping
Black from playing Ne7-Ng6 and getting a great position. White is not in time
to play f4.}) 8. Nd2 $1 {White needs to get f4 in as soon as possible!} (8. e5)
8... Bg7 (8... e5 $2 {Black is seriously lagging in development and cannot
afford such luxury. White opens the position fast and gets a decisive attack}
9. Nc4 Be6 10. f4 $1 Bxc4 11. dxc4 exf4 12. Bxf4 $16 {If Black manages to
finish his development and castle short, he will have a great game. However,
this is impossible: he simply lacks the tempi to do so. This line comes as an
example that White can choose among different strategies: playing against Bc8,
rapidly opening the position with f4, or going for a direct attack against
Black's king in the center.}) 9. f4 $1 $14 Ne7 10. Nf3 Ba6 11. Bd2 (11. e5 $1
d5 12. Na4 $3 {Again, White has the option to employ a dark-squared strategy!}
c4 13. Nc5 (13. d4 c3 14. Re1 cxb2 15. Bxb2 $16 O-O 16. Nc5 Bc4 17. g4) 13...
Qb6 (13... Bc8 14. d4 $1 $18) 14. Be3 $18 cxd3 15. cxd3) 11... O-O (11... c4 {
only chance to keep the balance} 12. d4 (12. dxc4 Bxc4 13. Re1) 12... d5 13. e5
O-O 14. Be3 $14) 12. b3 $1 {stopping c4} Rad8 (12... d5 13. e5 c4 14. dxc4 dxc4
15. b4 $1 {Black's bishop is still blocked}) 13. Qe1 (13. Na4 {is possible too}
d5 14. c4 dxe4 15. dxe4 Bxa1 16. Qxa1 {Black cannot guard all the weak dark
squares}) 13... Bb7 14. Ne2 $3 {[%cal Yc2c4]} (14. e5 d5 15. Na4 c4 16. d4 $18
(16. Ba5)) 14... d5 (14... Bxa1 15. Ba5 Qc8 16. Qxa1 $18 Rde8 17. Qf6) 15. c4
f5 (15... Bxa1 16. Ba5 ({Even} 16. Qxa1 {does not give Black any chances} d4
17. Qe1 $1 {White blocks Black's sole pawn break of a5-a4} (17. e5) 17... Ra8
18. Ba5 Qc8 19. Qh4 {White's initiative is decisive})) 16. e5 $18 {White is
completely winning as his opponent does not have a single active minor piece}
dxc4 17. dxc4 Qd7 18. Be3 Qd3 19. Kf2 {A funny move highlighting the fact that
Black plays with a queen and rook against White's whole army} Qd7 20. Qd1 Qc7
21. Qc2 Rd7 22. Rfd1 Rfd8 23. Rxd7 Rxd7 24. Rd1 Rxd1 25. Qxd1 Qb6 26. Nc3 Kf7
27. Na4 Qc7 28. Ng5+ Kg8 29. Nxe6 Qa5 30. Qd2 Qxd2+ 31. Bxd2 Kf7 32. Ng5+ Ke8
33. Ne6 Kf7 34. Nxg7 Kxg7 35. Nxc5 Bc8 36. Ba5 h6 37. Bd8 Ng8 38. g3 g5 39.
fxg5 hxg5 40. Bxg5 Kg6 41. h4 Nh6 42. Bxh6 Kxh6 43. Ke3 Kh5 44. Kf4 {
Guest2697229 gibt auf (Lag: Av=0.23s, max=0.5s)} 1-0

