{[%evp 0,93,18,28,51,45,48,50,52,31,31,17,28,-1,32,25,21,24,24,5,26,2,77,74,55,
65,71,35,55,50,46,36,-7,5,4,4,2,27,38,-31,-32,-31,-23,-23,-40,-53,-46,-46,-49,
-49,-47,-17,-24,-38,-44,-60,-17,-29,-36,-45,-18,-21,-21,-25,13,30,45,45,53,15,
54,15,10,19,41,0,0,-56,60,56,66,23,70,61,115,91,190,201,297,95,289,308,585,611,
664,711]} 1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. Bb5 e6 (3... Nd4 {is objectively the best move
}) 4. Bxc6 bxc6 (4... dxc6 {White's plans are very similar: he still develops
with f4, Nf3, etc., and ideally wants to push c4 at some point. Here is a
sample line to illustrate White's ideas:} 5. f4 Nf6 6. d3 Be7 7. Nf3 O-O 8. O-O
b6 9. Ne2 Bb7 10. c4 {The d3 pawn can easily be protected and is not a weakness
} Qc7 11. Nc3 Rad8 12. Qe2 Rd7 13. Be3 (13. Ne5) 13... Rfd8 14. Rad1 b5 15. b3
Rc8 16. Ne5 {Black is much worse on both sides of the board and will be under
dangerous attack after g4,g5, etc.} (16. e5) 16... Rdd8 17. g4) 5. d3 Ne7 (5...
d5 6. f4) (5... e5 6. f4 {White immediately undermines Black's center and gets
a small advantage because of the open f-file} (6. Nge2 {with the idea of
castling first and then pushing f4 is also possible}) (6. Nf3 $6 {is a
positional mistake as White cannot carry out his main idea with f4 anymore} d6)
6... exf4 7. Bxf4 d6 8. Nf3 Ne7 9. O-O Ng6 10. Bg3) (5... d5 6. Bd2 (6. f4 dxe4
7. dxe4 Qxd1+ 8. Nxd1 {The endgame is very unpleasant for Black because of his
compromised structure} Be7 (8... c4 {is Black's best bet}) 9. c4 Nf6 10. Nc3 {
White consolidates his position and is ready to attack c5 later in the game}
Ba6 11. b3 Nd7 12. Nf3 Bf6 13. Kd2 {White is not in a hurry- he just needs to
parry his opponent's threats and start attacking himself} Rd8 14. Kc2 O-O 15.
Be3 (15. e5))) 6. f4 d6 7. Nf3 g6 8. O-O Bg7 9. Kh1 (9. e5 dxe5 10. fxe5 {
[%cal Yc3e4,Ye4d6]} Bxe5 11. Nxe5 Qd4+ 12. Kh1 Qxe5 13. Ne4 $18 {Black has no
way of protecting the dark squares} Nf5 14. Bg5) 9... O-O 10. e5 d5 11. Na4 c4
12. dxc4 $6 (12. d4 $1 {[%csl Rc5,Rd6,Rf6] Switching to a dark-squared
strategy! Black's light-squared bishop is useless, and White will gradually
take over the dark squares} f6 ({Sample play to illustrate White's plan. The
moves played are not the most precise for both sides but rather show what
White's long-term goals are} 12... Ba6 13. Nc5 (13. c3 Bb5 14. Nc5 a5 15. Be3 (
15. g4) 15... Nf5 {Black cannot stop White from taking control over the dark
squares. Even though it will take time, White will accomplish his plan} 16. Bf2
h5 17. g3 (17. h3 h4 18. Qe1) 17... a4 18. a3 Rb8 19. Kg2 Qc7 20. h3 Rfe8 21.
g4 hxg4 22. hxg4 Ne7 23. Bh4)) 13. Nc5 Rb8 14. b3 $18 fxe5 15. fxe5 (15. Nxe5))
12... dxc4 {Black somewhat improved his position by opening the game} ({
Most likely White counted on:} 12... Ba6 13. b3 dxc4 14. Nc5 Qb6 15. Nd7) 13.
Qe2 Qa5 14. Nc3 $14 Nd5 (14... c5) 15. Ne4 c3 16. bxc3 Ba6 17. c4 Nb6 18. Nfd2
Rfd8 19. Rg1 Qa4 $15 20. Nc5 Bxc4 21. Qe4 Qb5 22. Nb7 Bd5 23. Qe3 Nc4 24. Nxc4
Qxb7 25. Nd2 c5 26. c4 Bc6 27. Rb1 Qc7 28. Rb3 Rab8 29. Bb2 Rxb3 30. Nxb3 Bf8
31. Ba3 Qd7 32. Bxc5 Bxc5 33. Qxc5 Ba8 34. h3 a6 35. Kh2 Qd3 36. Qb6 Kg7 37. c5
Rc8 38. Qa5 Qe4 39. Qd2 a5 40. Re1 Qa4 41. Rc1 Qe4 42. Nxa5 Rd8 43. Qf2 Rd4 44.
Nb3 Rd3 45. c6 Bxc6 46. Nc5 Qd4 47. Nxd3 1-0

