{[%evp 0,111,25,16,71,40,33,29,69,29,28,13,22,-22,-8,-10,3,5,12,-2,-2,-6,11,28,
48,48,33,37,44,46,40,40,36,36,57,33,39,65,62,82,75,91,91,95,112,40,54,79,118,
96,162,77,414,77,103,103,103,103,111,103,103,76,103,85,103,85,93,103,103,93,
103,103,113,98,99,118,123,132,133,125,118,118,111,135,117,122,122,143,130,145,
140,155,155,170,153,133,128,151,149,149,249,149,149,158,157,162,176,181,190,
217,208,232,236,247] A true positional masterpiece by the famous Russian
grandmaster! The game greatly exemplifies several themes: the weakness of the
doubled c-pawns, Na4 clearing the way for c2-c4, overprotection, and the
change of the structure at an opportune moment.} 1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. f4 (3.
Bb5 g6 4. Bxc6 bxc6 5. f4 Bg7 6. Nf3 d6 7. d3 {is another move order to
achieve the same position}) 3... g6 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. Bb5 d6 6. Bxc6+ bxc6 7. d3 f5
$2 (7... Bg4 {Black's best option, thus he solves the problems with his
light-squared bishop. However, White's position is still preferable due to his
more flexible structure} 8. O-O Nf6 9. h3 Bxf3 10. Qxf3 $16 Nd7 11. Rb1 {
Prophylaxis move: White protects b2 and continues developing} (11. Bd2 Qb6 12.
Rab1 c4+ 13. Kh1 cxd3 14. cxd3 $14) 11... Rb8 12. Bd2) 8. e5 {[%csl Rg8]
Obstructing Black's natural development} Nh6 9. Qe2 $1 {Overprotecting the
important e5 pawn and placing the queen on a good position} O-O 10. Bd2 Qb6 11.
Na4 $3 {Gaining a tempo and opening the path for c2-c4!} Qb5 12. b3 Nf7 13. c4
$1 $18 {After this move Black has no active play whatsoever} Qb8 14. Bc3 $3 {
Another prophylactic move improving the bishop} Nd8 15. g3 Ne6 16. h4 h5 17.
O-O-O Bd7 18. Rhe1 Nd4 (18... d5 {has no threat; White just ignores it and
continues with his own plan} 19. Ng5 (19. Qf2 d4 20. Bb2 (20. Ba5)) 19... Nxg5
(19... Nd4 20. Qf2) 20. hxg5 d4 21. Bb2 {Eventually, White will take the c5
pawn} Qb4 22. Kb1 e6 23. Qd2 Rfb8 24. Qc1 {[%csl Rc5][%cal Yb2a3]} (24. Qxb4
cxb4 25. Bxd4)) 19. Qf2 Nxf3 20. Qxf3 Qc7 21. Qf2 Rae8 22. Qd2 {Black is
helpless so White is not in a hurry} Bc8 23. Re2 (23. Rf1 Ba6 24. Qe2 Kh7 25.
Kb2 $2 Bb5 {Surprisingly, Black manages to exchange his bishop}) 23... Bd7 24.
Kc2 Qd8 25. Rde1 Bh6 26. Qc1 Bg7 27. Qd2 Qb8 28. Re3 Qd8 29. R1e2 Qb8 30. Qe1
Bh6 31. Ba1 Qd8 32. Kb1 Bg7 33. Bc3 Qb8 34. Bb2 Qd8 35. Qd2 Bc8 36. exd6 exd6
37. Bxg7 Kxg7 38. d4 $1 $18 {A great positional player always knows when to
alter the structure and change the course of the game!} Rxe3 39. Qxe3 cxd4 40.
Qxd4+ Qf6 41. Re7+ Rf7 42. Rxf7+ Kxf7 43. Qxa7+ Qe7 44. Qxe7+ Kxe7 45. Kc2 c5
46. Kc3 Bd7 47. Nb2 Kd8 48. b4 Kc7 49. a4 Bc6 50. Nd3 cxb4+ 51. Kxb4 Be4 52.
Nc1 Bb7 53. Nb3 Ba6 54. Nd4 Kd7 55. c5 Bf1 56. Nb5 1-0

