{A difficult example! What should White play?} 1. Rb1 $1 {White starts a long
plan to improve his pieces. Black has nothing to oppose it as his only active
piece is the rook which can be neutralized. White's idea is to exchange the
rooks and then bring the knight to a4 winning the c5 pawn. To do so, he needs
a series of maneuvers: Rb2 (forcing the rook to the first rank), Nb1 and Kb2
to evict it from a1, exchanging the rooks via Ra1, and finally bringing the
knight to a4 (Nd2-f3-g1-h3-f2-d1-b2-a4).} (1. Rc2 Ra1+ $1) 1... Kd7 2. Kc1 $3
Bb7 3. Rb2 $3 Ra1+ (3... Rxb2 $2 4. Kxb2 Kc7 5. Ndf3 Kb6 6. Ng1 Ka5 7. Ka3 Bc8
8. N1h3 Bd7 9. Nf2 Be8 10. Nd1 Bd7 11. Nb2 Be8 12. Na4 Bd7 13. Nxc5 Bc8 14. b4+
Kb6 15. Nb3) 4. Nb1 Kc7 5. Rf2 Kb6 6. Kb2 $1 Ra8 7. Nd2 Bc8 8. Rf1 Bd7 9. Ra1
$1 Rxa1 (9... Rb8 {White will again take his knight to a4, slowly but surely})
10. Kxa1 Ka5 11. Kb2 Kb4 12. Ndf3 Bc8 13. Ne1 $3 {chasing away Black's king
and playing Ka3 after} Bd7 14. Nc2+ Ka5 15. Ka3 Bc8 16. Ne1 Bd7 17. Nef3 Be8
18. Ng1 Bd7 19. N1h3 Bc8 20. Nf2 Bd7 21. Nd1 Be8 22. Nb2 Bd7 23. Na4 {A
masterpiece!} *

