{[%evp 0,27,31,24,56,38,47,43,43,36,49,25,25,18,34,19,22,23,16,8,48,48,40,47,
48,47,68,73,73,59]} 1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nd4 4. Nf3 a6 (4... e6 {A
tricky move that indirectly protects the d4 pawn in case of capture} 5. Bd3 {
The awkward position of the bishop on d3 is not a problem as White plans to
play Nxd4, c3 and dxc3 next.} (5. Nxd4 $2 cxd4 6. Ne2 Qg5 {White is in trouble}
) 5... Nc6 (5... a6 6. O-O (6. Nxd4 {does not work this time:} cxd4 7. Ne2 d5
8. O-O dxe4 9. Bxe4 Nf6 {Black has solved his opening troubles}) 6... Nc6 {
transposes into the main line with 4...a6} (6... Ne7 7. Nxd4 cxd4 8. Ne2 d5 {
Here, the pawn break is not as effective as before: Black can no longer put
the bishop on c5} 9. Re1 dxe4 10. Bxe4 {[%cal Yc2c3] White's pieces are better
placed})) (5... Ne7 {Black wants to connect his knights} 6. Nxd4 cxd4 7. Nb5
Nc6 8. c3 {White did not manage to win the d4 pawn but forced a favorable
exchange} dxc3 9. dxc3 a6 10. Nd4 Nxd4 (10... Be7 11. O-O O-O 12. Nxc6 dxc6 (
12... bxc6 13. Bf4 d5 14. Qe2 {[%cal Ya1d1] White has great activity and his
position is easier to navigate}) 13. e5 {[%csl Rc8] White gets attacking
potential on the kingside whereas Black struggles to develop his light-squared
bishop}) 11. cxd4 Bb4+ 12. Kf1 $1 {[%cal Yh2h4,Yh4h5] White keeps more pieces
on the board and prepares an attack on the kingside. The king is perfectly
safe on f1 and does not impede the coordination of the white army} (12. Bd2 {
simplifies the position too much} Qa5 13. a3 Bxd2+ 14. Qxd2 Qxd2+ 15. Kxd2)
12... Be7 13. h4 d6 14. g3 b5 15. Kg2 O-O 16. f3 Bb7 17. Be3 $14 {1/2 (36)
Kluegel,J (2509)-Koegler,K (2546) ICCF email 2018}) 6. O-O g6 (6... a6 {
transposes} 7. Nd5) (6... d6 7. Bb5 Bd7 (7... Nf6 $6 8. e5 dxe5 9. Nxe5 Qc7 10.
Nxc6 bxc6 11. Bc4 {Black pawn's structure is destroyed} Bd6 12. h3 O-O 13. d3 {
Black does not have any active counterplay and is stuck defending the c-pawns
for the rest of the game}) 8. Re1 Nf6 9. Bxc6 Bxc6 10. d4 cxd4 11. Nxd4 Rc8 12.
Nxc6 Rxc6 13. Nd5 $1 {Once again the typical idea! White does not allow Black
to develop naturally. For example,} Be7 14. Nxe7 Qxe7 {is favorable for a
White because the bishop is superior to the knight.} 15. b3 O-O 16. Ba3 {
[%cal Ye4e5]}) 7. Bb5 {White switches to Rossolimo plans} Bg7 (7... Nge7 {
The combination of e6 and g6 is very risky since it leaves the dark squares
mostly unprotected. White has the chance to grasp the initiative after:} 8. e5
Bg7 9. d4 (9. Ne4 {does not give White much} Nxe5 10. Nd6+ Kf8) (9. Bxc6 {
is another possibility} Nxc6 10. d4 cxd4 11. Ne4 Nxe5 12. Nd6+ Kf8 13. Nxd4 {
Black faces trouble finding good places for his pieces}) 9... cxd4 10. Ne4 $1
Nxe5 11. Nd6+ Kf8 12. Bf4 {White establishes firm control of the dark squares
and has good compensation}) 8. Bxc6 bxc6 9. e5 $16 {[%csl Rc5,Rd6,Re7] Locking
the bishop: White goes on to play Ne4 next move and exploit Black's weaknesses
in the center} f6 10. Ne4 fxe5 11. Nd6+ (11. Nxc5 {only misplaces the knight}
d6 {[%cal Yc6c5]}) 11... Kf8 (11... Ke7 12. Ng5 $1 {[%csl Rf7]} Nh6 13. Nge4 {
[%cal Yd2d3,Yc1e3] The inclusion of dark-squared bishop after d3 is decisive})
12. d3 Qc7 13. Nxc8 Rxc8 14. Be3 d6 15. Ng5 {White opens the f-file next move
and crashes through}) (4... g6 5. Nxd4 cxd4 6. Ne2 Bg7 7. c3 {White gets rid
of the strong d4 pawn to gain control of the central squares} a6 8. Bc4 {
The bishop finds another target in the face of f7} dxc3 9. dxc3 {The optimal
solution} (9. bxc3 {gives Black counterplay along the c-file in the future} b5
10. Bd5 Rb8 11. d3 {[%csl Rc3]} (11. d4 Nf6 {Black gets comfortable play after
trading the bishop})) 9... d6 (9... Nf6 10. e5) 10. Be3 Nf6 11. f3 O-O {
1-0 (96) Lazov,T (2405)-Frantz,N (2140) Europe Echecs INT 2021} 12. a4 $14 {
[%csl Rb6][%cal Ya4a5] White stops b5 and prepares to exploit the weakened
dark squares on the queenside} Bd7 13. a5 Rc8 14. Bb3 {White has a space
advantage and is slightly better}) (4... Nf6 {is of no independent value as
Black is forced to take Nxb5 after e5} 5. e5 Nxb5 6. Nxb5 Nd5 7. O-O {
transposes to 3...nxb5} a6 8. c4 $1 axb5 9. cxd5 {[%csl Rd7,Re7]} e6 (9... d6
10. d4 Bg4 11. Bf4 $18 Ra4 12. Be3 c4 13. b3 Ra8 14. a4 Rc8 15. axb5 c3 16. Ra4
g6 17. Rc4 Bg7 18. exd6 Qxd6 19. Ne5 Rxc4 20. Nxc4 Bxd1 21. Nxd6+ exd6 22. Rxd1
Kd7 23. Rc1 Ra8 {1/2 (23) Owen,L-Carey,M USA 1980}) 10. d6) 5. Bd3 {[%cal
Gf3d4,Gc3e2]} g6 (5... e6 {The most challenging continuation which I often
employed myself} 6. O-O (6. Nxd4 cxd4 7. Ne2 d5 $1 8. exd5 Qxd5) 6... Nc6 (6...
Ne7 7. Nxd4 cxd4 8. Ne2 Nc6 9. c3 Bc5 10. b4 Ba7 11. Bb2 dxc3 12. dxc3 O-O 13.
a3 d5 (13... d6 14. c4 e5 15. Kh1 Be6 16. f4 {1-0 (41) Safarli,E (2598)
-Oboladze,L (2405) Playchess.com INT 2020}) 14. exd5 exd5 15. Nf4 $14) (6...
Nxf3+ 7. Qxf3 Qc7 8. b3 $1 Bd6 9. Qh3 Ne7 10. Bb2 Be5 11. f4 Bxf4 12. Rxf4 Qxf4
13. Rf1 Qg5 14. e5 Qxe5 15. Na4 Qg5 16. Nb6 Rb8 17. Nc4 f6 18. Nd6+ Kf8 19. Ne4
Qh6 20. Rxf6+ Qxf6 21. Nxf6 gxf6 22. Bxf6 Rg8 23. Qxh7 Nd5 24. Bg6 Rxg6 25.
Qxg6 Nxf6 26. Qxf6+ Ke8 27. Qe5 Ra8 28. Qxc5 b5 29. Qc7 a5 30. h4 Ba6 31. h5
Ke7 32. h6 b4 33. Qe5 d6 34. Qg7+ {1-0 (34) Baskin,R (2398)-Zhigalko,S (2572)
Chess.com INT 2021}) (6... d6 $2 7. Nxd4 cxd4 8. Ne2 e5 9. c3 dxc3 10. dxc3 Nf6
11. c4 Be7 12. Nc3 $16 {1-0 (43) Stukopin,A (2555)-Ginsburg,M (2315) Redmond
2021}) 7. Nd5 $5 {Modern theory's suggestion to play the line! The idea behind
the move is that if Black accepts the material, he will struggle with his king
in the center and lack of development. The positional ideas behind the move
include preparing c3, Bc2, and d4 or b3, Bb2.} (7. Re1 {is the most common
move. However, Black has a creative solution to his opening problems:} g5 8. h3
h5 {Black rapidly organizes an attack on the kingside and forces White to
start defending}) 7... g6 (7... exd5 8. exd5 Nb4 9. Re1+) (7... d6 8. Ne3 {
White successfully regrouped and now prepares a break in the center} (8. Re1 $2
exd5 {White does not have compensation for the material:} 9. exd5+ Ne5 10. Nxe5
dxe5 11. Rxe5+ Be7) 8... Nf6 9. c3 {[%cal Gd3c2,Gd2d4]} d5 (9... Be7 10. Bc2
O-O 11. d4 cxd4 12. cxd4 e5 13. d5 {Black's pieces are heavily restricted}) 10.
exd5 Nxd5 11. Be4 Be7 12. d4 $14) 8. Re1 Bg7 9. c3 Nge7 (9... d6 10. Ne3 Nge7
11. Bc2 e5 12. b4 $5 cxb4 (12... b6 13. a3 O-O 14. Bb3 h6 {1/2 (25) Gabrielian,
A (2464)-Kryakvin,D (2567) Cheliabinsk 2022} 15. d3 Kh7 16. Rb1 $14) 13. a3
bxc3 14. dxc3 O-O 15. a4 $44 {[%cal Gc1a3]}) 10. Nxe7 Qxe7 11. Bc2 e5 12. d4
$14 d6 13. dxc5 dxc5 14. Be3 Bg4 15. Bb3 O-O 16. h3 Rfd8 17. Qe2 Bxf3 18. Qxf3
Rd7 19. Rad1 Rad8 20. Bd5 Na7 21. Qg4 Kh8 22. Bb3 b6 23. Rxd7 Rxd7 24. Rd1
Rxd1+ 25. Qxd1 Nb5 26. Qd5 Nd6 27. Qa8+ Bf8 28. Qxa6 Qc7 29. Qa8 Kg8 30. Bd5 h5
31. a4 Nc8 32. Qb7 Qxb7 33. Bxb7 Nd6 34. Bd5 Kg7 35. b4 Nc8 36. a5 bxa5 37.
bxa5 Bd6 38. Kf1 Kf6 39. Ke2 Ke7 40. Kd3 {1-0 (40) Jones,G (2670) -Navara,D  
(2697) Tornelo INT 2020}) (5... Nxf3+ {A dubious decision: Black exchanges his
only developed piece!} 6. Qxf3 d6 (6... e6 7. b3 Qc7 8. Bb2 Ne7 9. O-O Ng6 10.
Ne2 {White regroups his pieces and takes aim at Black's kingside} Bd6 11. Qh3
f6 {1/2 (28) Rapport,R (2698) -Gara,A (2373) Zalakaros 2017} 12. f4 $16 Nxf4
13. Nxf4 Bxf4 14. Qg4 $1 Bh6 (14... Bxh2+ 15. Kh1) 15. Bxf6 gxf6 16. Qh5+) 7.
O-O Nf6 8. b3 {[%cal Yc1b2,Yc3d5] posing concrete problems to Black} g6 9. Bb2
Bg7 10. Nd5 Bg4 11. Qg3 Nh5 12. Qxg4 Bxb2 13. Rae1 e6 (13... Bg7 14. f4 {
White has a promising attack}) 14. Ne3 {[%cal Gf2f4]}) (5... Nc6 6. O-O d6 7.
Bc4 e6 8. d4 cxd4 9. Nxd4 Nf6 {A famous theoretical position where I like the
rare:} 10. Nxc6 $5 bxc6 11. Bf4 d5 12. Bd3 Be7 13. Qf3 O-O 14. Na4 $14 {
[%cal Gc2c4]} Bb7) (5... d6 6. Nxd4 cxd4 7. Ne2 e5 8. c3 dxc3 9. dxc3 Nf6 10.
c4 $16 {[%csl Rd6][%cal Ge2c3] Black is left with a permanent weakness on d6})
(5... b5 6. Nxd4 cxd4 7. Ne2 e5 8. c3 dxc3 9. dxc3 Nf6 10. a4 bxa4 11. Rxa4 Bb7
12. O-O Be7 13. Ng3 $16) 6. Rb1 $5 (6. Nxd4 cxd4 7. Ne2 d5 $1 (7... Bg7 8. c3
dxc3 (8... d5 9. Nxd4 dxe4 10. Bxe4 Bxd4 {0-1 (54) Sanal,V (2601)-Macovei,A  
(2454) Chess.com INT 2021} 11. Qa4+ $1 Qd7 12. Qxd7+ Bxd7 13. cxd4 $14) 9. dxc3
d6) 8. c3 dxc3 9. bxc3 dxe4 10. Bxe4 Nf6 11. Bf3 Bg7 12. O-O O-O 13. d4 Bg4)
6... Nc6 (6... d6 7. b4 Bg4 8. bxc5 dxc5 9. Rxb7 Qc8 10. Rb6 Bxf3 11. gxf3 Qh3
12. Be2) (6... Bg7 7. b4 cxb4 8. Rxb4 Nc6 9. Rb1 Nf6 10. Bb2 O-O 11. Nd5 e6 12.
Nxf6+ Bxf6 13. Bxf6 Qxf6 14. Rb6 d5 15. O-O $14 {1/2 (30) Firouzja,A (2669)
-Cornette,M (2556) Reykjavik 2019}) 7. a3 Bg7 (7... b5 8. b4 c4 9. Be2 Bg7 10.
Bb2 Nf6 11. d3 cxd3 {1-0 (27) Sanal,V (2563) -Nazaretyan,T (2277) Tallinn 2019}
12. Qxd3 O-O 13. Nd5 d6 14. c4 $14) 8. b4 cxb4 9. axb4 b5 10. Be2 d6 {0-1 (23)
Bettalli,F (2305)-Solomon,K (2354) Imola 2021} 11. d4 Bg4 12. Be3 Nf6 13. h3
Bxf3 14. Bxf3 $14 *

