{[%evp 0,67,31,35,47,36,32,36,44,36,42,42,42,42,34,56,51,47,47,38,45,41,47,60,
87,53,27,26,277,268,554,628,639,350,347,347,440,259,271,282,268,249,300,296,
293,268,410,385,875,613,642,659,659,571,562,562,494,608,608,403,337,360,341,
351,656,656,862,905,924,913]} 1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 (2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. Nc3 Nd4
5. e5 Nxb5 6. Nxb5 Nd5 {transposes}) 2... Nc6 3. Bb5 Nd4 {The most critical
move that is often seen at the highest level. Black avoids the doubling of his
pawns and threatens White's bishop pair.The drawback is that Black loses
another tempo playing with the same piece instead of continuing his
development.} 4. Nf3 {Black is at a crossroad: either exchange the bishop and
try to catch up with White's development advantage or restrict the bishop with
a6} Nxb5 5. Nxb5 {Black has to choose between different setups- immediately
evict the the annoying Nb5, develop with Nf6 or break the center with d5} d5 {
A most ambitious try by Black!} (5... Nf6 {This position is very popular as it
can arise from the Rossolimo as well} 6. e5 Nd5 7. O-O a6 {By far, Black's
most sensible choice- he needs to get rid of the knight in order to play e6
and complete his development} 8. c4 $1 {An important intermediate move thst
keeps the fight for an opening advantage} ({The natural} 8. Nc3 $6 {does not
give White anything. After} Nxc3 9. bxc3 d5 {, Black gets an excellent
position with a strong light-squared bishop.}) 8... Nb4 {Black's best option} (
8... axb5 {is nearly lost for Black. It is practically impossible for him to
develop his pieces due to White's far advanced central points} 9. cxd5 {
[%csl Rd7,Re7]} d6 10. d4 cxd4 11. e6 fxe6 12. Nxd4 exd5 13. Qh5+ g6 14. Qxd5 {
[%csl Rd7,Re6,Rf7] Black's position is in ruins: there is no hope for him to
withstand White's coming attack.}) (8... Nc7 9. Nxc7+ Qxc7 10. d4 {White has
big advantage in development and looks to open lines and diagonals against the
enemy king} cxd4 11. Qxd4 e6 12. Rd1 $16 Bc5 13. Qg4 {[%csl Rg7] The queen
swings over the fourth rank to harass the weakened kingside. The e5 pawn
guarantees White great attacking potential as it prevents Black's army from
coming to defend the king.}) 9. Nc3 {The inclusion of c4 enabled White to get
control of the important d5 square} d6 10. d4 (10. exd6 Qxd6 11. Ne4 Qc7 12. d4
cxd4 13. Re1 Bg4 14. Qa4+ Nc6 15. Nxd4 O-O-O 16. Nxc6 Qxc6 {1/2 (28) Kornyukov,
A (2420) -Kalugin,S (2362) Azov 2007} 17. Qa5 $1 $146 e6 18. Be3 $40) 10...
cxd4 11. Qxd4 {A fascinating line where White sacrifices material to build up
initiative!} Nc2 12. Qe4 Nxa1 13. Bf4 {White is now down only an exchange and
keeps a very active position. In a practical game, he has excellent chances as
Black needs to play with the level of precision of an engine just to keep the
balance} Be6 14. Rxa1 (14. Ng5) 14... Rc8 15. Nd5 dxe5 16. Nxe5 f6 17. Nf3 Bxd5
18. cxd5 Rc5 19. d6 Qd7 20. b4 Rc6 21. Re1 Kf7 22. Nd4 e5 23. Qd5+ Kg6 24. Bxe5
Rxd6 25. Bxd6 Bxd6 26. Qe4+ Kf7 27. Qd5+ Kg6 28. g3 h6 29. Rd1 Re8 30. Nf3 Re6
31. Nh4+ Kh7 32. Qd3+ {1-0 (32) Firouzja,A (2754) -Rapport,R (2760) Stavanger
2021}) (5... a6 6. Nc3 d6 {holds no independent value: the game is most likely
going to transpose to one of the lines above} (6... b5 7. d4 cxd4 8. Qxd4 e6 (
8... Bb7 $6 9. a4 {Black has overextended on the queenside and White uses the
chance to undermine his structure} bxa4 10. Nxa4 Nf6 {[%cal Ya4b6,Ya4c5]} 11.
Nb6 Rb8 12. Bf4 d6 13. O-O-O $18 {[%cal Ye4e5,Yh1e1]} Bxe4 14. Qa4+) 9. Bf4 $1
(9. Bg5 Qc7 10. O-O-O f6 11. Be3 Bb7) 9... Bb7 10. O-O-O Nf6 11. Rhe1 Be7 (
11... Rc8 12. Qa7 Rxc3 13. Qxb7 Qc8 14. Qxc8+ Rxc8 15. Kb1 Bc5 16. Re2 {
[%csl Rd7]}) 12. Bd6 O-O 13. Ne5 Re8 14. Re3 Bxd6 15. Qxd6 $14 {1/2 (47)
Plaskett,H (2497) -Mikkelsen,N (2417) Palma de Mallorca 2013}) 7. d4 cxd4 8.
Qxd4 e5 (8... Nf6 $6 {is a variation we have already examined} 9. Bg5 e6 10.
O-O-O Be7 11. e5 dxe5 12. Qxe5 Qb6 13. Ne4 $18) 9. Qb4 $1 {A perfect square
for the queen from where it assists the attack on the dark squares} (9. Qd3 {
is not as good here. Black is able to prevent Bg5 and develop harmoniously} Be7
10. O-O Be6 11. Nd5 Bxd5 12. Qxd5 Qc7 {Black is in time to organize
counterplay against the e4 pawn after Nf6 and Qc6}) 9... h6 (9... Nf6 10. Bg5 {
[%csl Rd5]} d5 11. Qb3 d4 12. Bxf6 gxf6 13. Nd5 $14) (9... d5 {fails
tactically:} 10. Qb3 d4 11. Nxe5 Be6 12. Nd5 $16) (9... Ne7 10. O-O Nc6 11. Qb3
Na5 12. Qd5 Be6 13. Qd2 Be7 (13... Nc4 14. Qd3 Nb6 15. b3 Be7 16. a4 Rc8 17.
Ne2 O-O 18. c4 $14) 14. b3 b5 15. Nd5 $14 {1-0 (43) Liang,J (2342) -Tsyganov,I
